{"title_page": "Anthony Mora (public relations)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Anthony Mora\n| image       = Anthony_Mora,_Publicist,_Playwright.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Anthony Mora\n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Public Relations]], [[Playwright]]\n| website = http://www.anthonymora.com\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Mora''' is a [[Los Angeles]] [[publicist]],<ref name=Morabio>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/02/business/preludes-reality-television-vs-real-careers.html?pagewanted=2 |title=PRELUDES; Reality Television Vs. Real Careers |newspaper=The New York Times |date=2003-11-02|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> former [[journalist]] and [[magazine editor]], [[entrepreneur]], [[author]], [[playwright]], and [[screenwriter]].\n\n==Public Relations==\n\nAnthony Mora is the founder of [[Los Angeles]]-based Anthony Mora Communications, a private company in the PR Agencies industry.<ref>[http://www.business.com/company-L2xvh/anthony-mora-communications-los-angeles-ca/ [[Business.com]] Profile]</ref> Founded in 1990, the agency specializes in media placement, [[Corporate image|image development]], [[SEO]], [[social media]] and [[media training]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nightingale.com/Auth_Bio.aspx?author=Anthony_Mora |title=Nightingale-Conant presents Anthony Mora |publisher=Nightingale Conant |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130080637/http://www.nightingale.com/Auth_Bio.aspx?author=Anthony_Mora |archive-date=2013-01-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs a [[public relations]] and [[media relations]] expert,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/dec/05/business/fi-40656 |title=Wardrobe Stylist Hopes to Dress With Greater Success |work=[[LA Times]] |date=1999-12-09|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> Mora has been featured in a number of media outlets including ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/11/health/medicine-promotes-itself-with-professional-help.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Medicine Promotes Itself, With Professional Help |newspaper=The New York Times |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jan/21/news/wp-14990 |title=Self-Published Author May Discover Story of Her Life Can Be Tough Sell |work=[[LA Times]] |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[CNN]], the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://topstorypublicrelations.com/about/ |title=About Anthony Mora |publisher=Top Story PR |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806013718/http://topstorypublicrelations.com/about/ |archive-date=2012-08-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His firm represents clients in fields including [[health]],<ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diabetesoptions.net/common/pdfs/PPO021599.pdf |title=Physicians Find Success Building Niche Practices (PDF) |publisher=Physician Practice Options, February 15, 1999 |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110182030/http://www.diabetesoptions.net/common/pdfs/PPO021599.pdf |archive-date=November 10, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[beauty]], [[law]], [[publishing]], [[film]], [[entertainment]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/187752/why-is-tom-cruise-way-more-lovable-right-now |title=Why Is Tom Cruise Way More Lovable Right Now? |publisher=[[E! Online]] |date=2010-06-26|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> [[technology]], and [[business]].\n\nAnthony Mora Communications, Inc. has represented clients including The J Sisters, [[Hackensack University Medical Center]],  The Abi Fashion Collection and The Charles Winston Collection, [[Chuck Henry]], [[HarperCollins]] and [[Putnam Publishing]].<ref name=Case>{{cite web |url=http://www.anthonymora.com/case_studies.html |title=Anthony Mora Communications, Inc. Case Studies |publisher=Anthony Mora's Homepage |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726005814/http://www.anthonymora.com/case_studies.html |archive-date=2012-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The firm has placed clients in a wide range of media outlets, including ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', [[CNN]], ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', the ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'', and hundreds of other local, national, and international media outlets.<ref name=Case/>\n\nIn 2002, Mora won the Irwin Award for Book Publicist of the Year (Best Fiction Campaign).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookpublicists.org/pages/IRWIN_winners.asp |title=The IRWIN Award Winners |publisher=BookPublicists.org |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\nMora's clients in the film industry have included [[Paramount Pictures]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/ |title=Michelle Gomez: Resume (1994 Anthony Mora Communications/Public Relations) |publisher=Reality Staff |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116235648/http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/ |archive-date=2013-01-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Bigfoot Entertainment]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigfoot.com.hk/pdf/MidnightMovie-mediakit.pdf |title=Midnight Movie for Bigfoot Entertainment: Media Kit |publisher=[[Bigfoot Entertainment]] |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> [[Mitch Anderson (director)|Mitch Anderson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/|title=Anthony Mora Communications: Testimonials|accessdate=2012-08-13|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116235648/http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/|archive-date=2013-01-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Hilary Henkin]], and actresses [[Roxana Brusso]] and [[Holly Hunter]].\n\nMora also works with a number of artists from painters and sculptors to authors, directors and designers. He leads a program titled \"P.R. For Artists\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prforartists.com/the-art-of-pr/ |title=The Art of P.R. |publisher= PR for Artists |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nMora is the author of two [[non-fiction]] books, including:\n\n* ''The Alchemy of Success'' ([[motivational]], [[management]], [[leadership]]; 1997).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openisbn.com/isbn/9780935016215/ |title=''The Alchemy of Success'' |publisher=Zinn Communications |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> {{ISBN|978-0-935016-21-5}}\n* ''Spin to Win'' ([[advertising]], [[marketing]], [[investing]]; 2003)\u2014Mora's \"Zen of media relations,\" which offers essential truths about getting the media to pay attention to you and/or your company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-102208043.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031342/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-102208043.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2016-03-04 |title=BOOK REVIEW: There's much to gain from Spin to Win |publisher=PR Week (US) via [[HighBeam Research]] |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://openisbn.com/isbn/1930709285/ |title=''Spin to Win'' |publisher=Hawk Publishing Group |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> {{ISBN|978-1-930709-28-7}}\n\n==Plays==\nIn 2006, Anthony served as the playwright-in-residence at The Sidewalk Studio Theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidewalkstudiotheatre.com/comingsoon.html |title=Anthony Mora's New Play To Premiere At The Sidewalk Studio Theatre In 2009 |publisher=The Sidewalk Studio Theatre |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> The theatre produced Anthony's play, ''P.O.P.: The Principles of Perfection'', and the world premiere of the full play of ''Bang! A Love Story''.<ref name=Goldstar>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldstar.com/events/burbank-ca/modern-love |title=Anthony Mora Bio |publisher=[[Goldstar Events]] |date=2009-02-17 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\nMora is the author of five plays:\n\n* ''Bang! A Love Story'' (Dragonon Incorporated; 2005).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LGvwAAAACAAJ&source=gbs_book_other_versions |title=Bang! A Love Story, ''Google Books'' |publisher=Dragonon Incorporated |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> {{ISBN|978-0-9763398-4-7}} Scenes from the [[controversial]], award-winning ''Bang!'' featuring ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' actress [[Linda Cardellini]] were performed at the Acme Theater in Los Angeles and [[The American Place Theater]] in New York.<ref name=Goldstar/> ''Bang!'' features characters whose core values are upended by youth, and was described in an ''[[LA Times]]'' review as \"a blend of [[Vladimir Nabokov]] and [[Bret Easton Ellis]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/content/printVersion/48044/ |title=Sex, God and Little Armenians |work=[[LA Times]] |date=2006-08-24 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n* ''P.O.P.: The Principles of Perfection'' (2006) spotlights America's obsession with [[popular culture|pop culture]], [[pop stars]], [[pop psychology]] and pop transformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://la.indymedia.org/calendar/event_display_detail.php?event_id=3632 |title=P.O.P.: The Principles of Perfection |publisher=LA [[Independent Media Center]] |date=2006-06-09|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n* ''Modern Love'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-02-05/calendar/modern-love/ |title=Modern Love |work=[[LA Weekly]] |date=2009-02-05|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> follows one of [[Hollywood]]'s most successful blockbuster [[Film producer|producer]]s, whose obsession with his directorial debut takes him down a dark, precarious path.<ref name=Goldstar/>\n* ''Silencing Silas'' (2012) is a [[one act]] [[Film noir|noir]] play that features a lethal female lead.<ref name=Tolucan>{{cite web |url=http://tolucantimes.info/section/theatre_review/silencing-silas-a-play-previewing-a-film/ |title=Silencing Silas&nbsp;... A Play Previewing a Film |work=[[The Tolucan Times]] |date=2012-06-07 |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130417201053/http://tolucantimes.info/section/theatre_review/silencing-silas-a-play-previewing-a-film/ |archive-date=2013-04-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''Hang Fire'' (2012) is suffused with Mora's trademark edgy, dark humor. It explores the shadow side of sex and power through a sex therapy group turned private revenge clique set on a dangerous vigilante mission.<ref name=Tolucan/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonymora.com Official Website of Anthony Mora Communications]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YA_14w--45g Interview with [[KTLA]] Morning Show]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303214927/http://www.popculturepassionistas.com/2012/05/antony-mora-from-publicist-to.html Interview with Anthony Mora] on his playwriting\n* [http://www.patheos.com/blogs/prophetormadman/about/steve-allen-bio/ Steve Allen Bio: \"Thank you&nbsp;... to Anthony Mora for being my media mentor\"]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mora, Anthony}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:American public relations people]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Media industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Anthony Mora\n| image       = Anthony_Mora,_Publicist,_Playwright.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Anthony Mora\n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  = [[Public Relations]], [[Playwright]]\n| website = http://www.anthonymora.com\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Mora''' is a [[Los Angeles]] [[publicist]],<ref name=Morabio>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/02/business/preludes-reality-television-vs-real-careers.html?pagewanted=2 |title=PRELUDES; Reality Television Vs. Real Careers |newspaper=New York Times |date=2003-11-02|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> former [[journalist]] and [[magazine editor]], [[entrepreneur]], [[author]], [[playwright]], and [[screenwriter]].\n\n==Public Relations==\n\nAnthony Mora is the founder of [[Los Angeles]]-based Anthony Mora Communications, a private company in the PR Agencies industry.<ref>[http://www.business.com/company-L2xvh/anthony-mora-communications-los-angeles-ca/ [[Business.com]] Profile]</ref> Founded in 1990, the agency specializes in media placement, [[Corporate image|image development]], [[SEO]], [[social media]] and [[media training]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nightingale.com/Auth_Bio.aspx?author=Anthony_Mora |title=Nightingale-Conant presents Anthony Mora |publisher=Nightingale Conant |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130080637/http://www.nightingale.com/Auth_Bio.aspx?author=Anthony_Mora |archive-date=2013-01-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs a [[public relations]] and [[media relations]] expert,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/dec/05/business/fi-40656 |title=Wardrobe Stylist Hopes to Dress With Greater Success |work=[[LA Times]] |date=1999-12-09|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> Mora has been featured in a number of media outlets including the ''[[New York Times]]'',<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/11/health/medicine-promotes-itself-with-professional-help.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm |title=Medicine Promotes Itself, With Professional Help |newspaper=New York Times |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/jan/21/news/wp-14990 |title=Self-Published Author May Discover Story of Her Life Can Be Tough Sell |work=[[LA Times]] |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> the ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', [[CNN]], the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://topstorypublicrelations.com/about/ |title=About Anthony Mora |publisher=Top Story PR |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120806013718/http://topstorypublicrelations.com/about/ |archive-date=2012-08-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His firm represents clients in fields including [[health]],<ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diabetesoptions.net/common/pdfs/PPO021599.pdf |title=Physicians Find Success Building Niche Practices (PDF) |publisher=Physician Practice Options, February 15, 1999 |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110182030/http://www.diabetesoptions.net/common/pdfs/PPO021599.pdf |archive-date=November 10, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[beauty]], [[law]], [[publishing]], [[film]], [[entertainment]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/187752/why-is-tom-cruise-way-more-lovable-right-now |title=Why Is Tom Cruise Way More Lovable Right Now? |publisher=[[E! Online]] |date=2010-06-26|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> [[technology]], and [[business]].\n\nAnthony Mora Communications, Inc. has represented clients including The J Sisters, [[Hackensack University Medical Center]],  The Abi Fashion Collection and The Charles Winston Collection, [[Chuck Henry]], [[HarperCollins]] and [[Putnam Publishing]].<ref name=Case>{{cite web |url=http://www.anthonymora.com/case_studies.html |title=Anthony Mora Communications, Inc. Case Studies |publisher=Anthony Mora's Homepage |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726005814/http://www.anthonymora.com/case_studies.html |archive-date=2012-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The firm has placed clients in a wide range of media outlets, including ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[60 Minutes]]'', ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', [[CNN]], ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', the ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'', and hundreds of other local, national, and international media outlets.<ref name=Case/>\n\nIn 2002, Mora won the Irwin Award for Book Publicist of the Year (Best Fiction Campaign).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookpublicists.org/pages/IRWIN_winners.asp |title=The IRWIN Award Winners |publisher=BookPublicists.org |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\nMora's clients in the film industry have included [[Paramount Pictures]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/ |title=Michelle Gomez: Resume (1994 Anthony Mora Communications/Public Relations) |publisher=Reality Staff |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116235648/http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/ |archive-date=2013-01-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Bigfoot Entertainment]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigfoot.com.hk/pdf/MidnightMovie-mediakit.pdf |title=Midnight Movie for Bigfoot Entertainment: Media Kit |publisher=[[Bigfoot Entertainment]] |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> [[Mitch Anderson (director)|Mitch Anderson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/|title=Anthony Mora Communications: Testimonials|accessdate=2012-08-13|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130116235648/http://www.anthonymora.com/pr/clients/testimonials/|archive-date=2013-01-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Hilary Henkin]], and actresses [[Roxana Brusso]] and [[Holly Hunter]].\n\nMora also works with a number of artists from painters and sculptors to authors, directors and designers. He leads a program titled \"P.R. For Artists\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prforartists.com/the-art-of-pr/ |title=The Art of P.R. |publisher= PR for Artists |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nMora is the author of two [[non-fiction]] books, including:\n\n* ''The Alchemy of Success'' ([[motivational]], [[management]], [[leadership]]; 1997).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.openisbn.com/isbn/9780935016215/ |title=''The Alchemy of Success'' |publisher=Zinn Communications |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> {{ISBN|978-0-935016-21-5}}\n* ''Spin to Win'' ([[advertising]], [[marketing]], [[investing]]; 2003)\u2014Mora's \"Zen of media relations,\" which offers essential truths about getting the media to pay attention to you and/or your company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-102208043.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031342/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-102208043.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2016-03-04 |title=BOOK REVIEW: There's much to gain from Spin to Win |publisher=PR Week (US) via [[HighBeam Research]] |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://openisbn.com/isbn/1930709285/ |title=''Spin to Win'' |publisher=Hawk Publishing Group |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> {{ISBN|978-1-930709-28-7}}\n\n==Plays==\nIn 2006, Anthony served as the playwright-in-residence at The Sidewalk Studio Theatre.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sidewalkstudiotheatre.com/comingsoon.html |title=Anthony Mora's New Play To Premiere At The Sidewalk Studio Theatre In 2009 |publisher=The Sidewalk Studio Theatre |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> The theatre produced Anthony's play, ''P.O.P.: The Principles of Perfection'', and the world premiere of the full play of ''Bang! A Love Story''.<ref name=Goldstar>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldstar.com/events/burbank-ca/modern-love |title=Anthony Mora Bio |publisher=[[Goldstar Events]] |date=2009-02-17 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n\nMora is the author of five plays:\n\n* ''Bang! A Love Story'' (Dragonon Incorporated; 2005).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LGvwAAAACAAJ&source=gbs_book_other_versions |title=Bang! A Love Story, ''Google Books'' |publisher=Dragonon Incorporated |date= |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> {{ISBN|978-0-9763398-4-7}} Scenes from the [[controversial]], award-winning ''Bang!'' featuring ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' actress [[Linda Cardellini]] were performed at the Acme Theater in Los Angeles and [[The American Place Theater]] in New York.<ref name=Goldstar/> ''Bang!'' features characters whose core values are upended by youth, and was described in an ''[[LA Times]]'' review as \"a blend of [[Vladimir Nabokov]] and [[Bret Easton Ellis]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/content/printVersion/48044/ |title=Sex, God and Little Armenians |work=[[LA Times]] |date=2006-08-24 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n* ''P.O.P.: The Principles of Perfection'' (2006) spotlights America's obsession with [[popular culture|pop culture]], [[pop stars]], [[pop psychology]] and pop transformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://la.indymedia.org/calendar/event_display_detail.php?event_id=3632 |title=P.O.P.: The Principles of Perfection |publisher=LA [[Independent Media Center]] |date=2006-06-09|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref>\n* ''Modern Love'' (2009)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-02-05/calendar/modern-love/ |title=Modern Love |work=[[LA Weekly]] |date=2009-02-05|accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> follows one of [[Hollywood]]'s most successful blockbuster [[Film producer|producer]]s, whose obsession with his directorial debut takes him down a dark, precarious path.<ref name=Goldstar/>\n* ''Silencing Silas'' (2012) is a [[one act]] [[Film noir|noir]] play that features a lethal female lead.<ref name=Tolucan>{{cite web |url=http://tolucantimes.info/section/theatre_review/silencing-silas-a-play-previewing-a-film/ |title=Silencing Silas&nbsp;... A Play Previewing a Film |work=[[The Tolucan Times]] |date=2012-06-07 |accessdate=2012-08-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130417201053/http://tolucantimes.info/section/theatre_review/silencing-silas-a-play-previewing-a-film/ |archive-date=2013-04-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''Hang Fire'' (2012) is suffused with Mora's trademark edgy, dark humor. It explores the shadow side of sex and power through a sex therapy group turned private revenge clique set on a dangerous vigilante mission.<ref name=Tolucan/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.anthonymora.com Official Website of Anthony Mora Communications]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YA_14w--45g Interview with [[KTLA]] Morning Show]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303214927/http://www.popculturepassionistas.com/2012/05/antony-mora-from-publicist-to.html Interview with Anthony Mora] on his playwriting\n* [http://www.patheos.com/blogs/prophetormadman/about/steve-allen-bio/ Steve Allen Bio: \"Thank you&nbsp;... to Anthony Mora for being my media mentor\"]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mora, Anthony}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:American public relations people]]\n[[Category:American dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Media industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Alaney2k", "label": "safe", "comment": "names of newspapers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Mora_(public_relations)"}
{"title_page": "1913 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1913 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1913 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1913 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1913 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after fifteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 29 June \u2013 27 July\n| stages             = 15\n| distance           = 5287\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 197h 54' 00\"\n| first              = [[Philippe Thys]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_team         = Peugeot\n| second             = [[Gustave Garrigou]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| second_team        = Peugeot\n| third              = [[Marcel Buysse]]\n| third_nat          = BEL\n| third_team         = Peugeot\n| previous           = [[1912 Tour de France|1912]]\n| next               = [[1914 Tour de France|1914]]\n}}\nThe '''1913 Tour de France''' was the 11th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place between 29 June and 27 July. The total distance was {{convert|5287|km|mi}} and the average speed of the riders was {{convert|26.715|km/h|mph}}.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} The competition was won by the [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Philippe Thys]], after in the crucial sixth stage [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]] broke his bicycle and lost several hours because he had to do the repairs by himself. In the last stage, Thys also had mechanical problems, but he got help during the repairs, and only got a penalty of ten minutes.\n\nBetween 1904 and 1912, the overall classification had been calculated by points, but in 1913 the classification was reverted to the original format from 1903, where the overall classification was calculated by adding up the times of the individual stages. The general classification has been calculated in the time format ever since.\n\n==Innovations and changes==\nIn 1905, the format of the Tour de France had been changed from the time system to the points system, to reduce the cheating that had caused the first four cyclists of the 1904 Tour de France to be disqualified. In the 1912 Tour de France, this system had been working against [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]'s chances, who would have been leading the time classification up until the final stage where he allowed a group to ride away.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1912.php |title=1912: Belgian victory foreshadows problems to come |publisher=VeloArchive |author=Tom James |date=14 August 2003 |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvybhFd?url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1912.php |archive-date=14 May 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> The system had been working against a French cyclist and in favor of a Belgian cyclist ([[Odiel Defraye]], who won the Tour de France in 1912), and the French organisation changed the system back again to the time system: the finishing times of all stages were added per cyclist, and the cyclist with the least total time was the winner. This was also intended to increase combativity, because in the points system riders did not care about time gaps, so escaped low-ranked riders were ignored by high-ranked cyclists.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|p=38}}\n\nFor the first time, the route of the race was in the opposite direction. Prior to the 1913 race, the Tour the France always had been in the clockwise direction through France, and in 1913 it was anticlockwise.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1913 Tour de France}}\n\nThe 1913 Tour started with 140 cyclists; there were 51 cyclists distributed over 9 teams, including all favourites for the overall victory. The remaining 89 cyclists started in the isol\u00e9s category.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/> This edition started with six former Tour de France winners ([[Louis Trousselier]], [[Lucien Petit-Breton]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], [[Octave Lapize]], [[Gustave Garrigou]] and [[Odile Defraye]]), the most ever.<ref name=\"veloarchive1913\"/>\n\nAlthough cyclists had started in teams previously, the rules had forbidden them to work together against other cyclists. In 1913, this changed, and cyclists from the same team were allowed to work together. The organisers preferred riders to ride solo, so they added a rule that if a cyclist would win a stage with a margin of 20 minutes or more, he would not only get his own prize money, but also the half of all the other cyclists' prize money of that stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.historischekranten.be/issue/DPO/1913-06-29/edition/null/page/2?query=%22ronde%20van%20frankrijk%22&period=1903-1939&sort=issuedate%20ascending|title=De ronde van Frankrijk|language=Dutch|date=29 June 1913|accessdate=20 May 2014|work=De Poperinghenaar}}</ref>\n\nThe first African cyclist took part in the Tour de France in 1913: [[Ali Neffati]] from Tunisia. Neffati had been discovered by Tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]], and would later become a driver at ''[[l'Auto]]'', the newspaper that organised the Tour de France.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8|1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15}}\n\n[[File:27-7-13 Tour de France Thys.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Philippe Thys]], winner of the 1913 Tour de France, after finishing the race]]\nIn the first stages, not much happened in the overall classification, as most cyclists were saving their energy for the Pyrenees.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=18\u201319}} The stage was won by Italian [[Giovanni Micheletto]] in a sprint. Micheletto was not part of the first group in the second stage, and thus lost his lead. There were four cyclists who had been in the lead group in both stages, and they were jointly leading the Tour.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=1&mod=krantresultaat&q=masselis&datering=7/1913&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=datum+asc%2Ckrant+asc%2Cpagina+asc&paragraaf=70&doc=6&p=3&paragraaf=96&y=376|title=De algemeene klassering na de twee eerste ritten|language=Dutch|date=3 July 1913|accessdate=20 October 2013|publisher=Documentatiecentrum en Archief voor Daensisme en Hedendaagse Geschiedenis van de Denderstreek|work=De Volksstem|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022063042/http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=1&mod=krantresultaat&q=masselis&datering=7%2F1913&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=datum+asc%2Ckrant+asc%2Cpagina+asc&paragraaf=70&doc=6&p=3&paragraaf=96&y=376|archive-date=22 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe most important event occurred in the third stage, when former winner Lapize stopped the race; either because he considered his earning insufficient,<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1913/histoire.html |title=1913 - 11th Tour de France |publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]] |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvzQdR4?url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1913/us/annee.html |archive-date=14 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> or because he thought his team was not good enough.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|p=38}}\n\nThe crucial stage proved to be the sixth. At the start of the sixth stage, last year's winner Defraye lead the general classification, some 5 minutes ahead of [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]].{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|p=38}} In that sixth stage, the first mountains were climbed. Defraye was dropped quickly, and Christophe lead the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive1913\"/> Christophe came up first on the Aubisque, and in second place behind [[Philippe Thys]] on the [[Tourmalet]]. On the way down from the Tourmalet, Christophe was hit by a race vehicle,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2007/jan/07/cycling.features|title=There's unlucky ... and then there's Christophe|first=Matt|last=Rendell|date=7 January 2007|accessdate=17 December 2015|publisher=[[theguardian.com]]}}</ref> and his fork broke, rendering his bike unusable, and the rules said that he had to repair it himself. He walked more than 10&nbsp;km down to the next village, and found a place where he could repair his bicycle. He worked on it for over three hours, being watched by race officials who made sure that he was not helped by anyone. When Christophe asked a small boy, of seven years old, to work the [[bellows]], he was fined with ten minutes.<ref name=\"veloarchive1913\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1913.php|title=1913: Eug\u00e8ne Christophe, Ste. Marie de Campan and the forge|author=Tom James|publisher=VeloArchive|date=14 August 2003| accessdate= 12 May 2009}}</ref><ref>Strack, F. (February 2019). Power to the people?: The rise of the e-bike causes Frank Strack to consider the essence of what it means to be a cyclist. ''Cyclist:The Thrill of the Ride'', (83), 48.</ref> During this repair, angry with the draconian rules, he snapped: (at the hungry race commissaires) \"If you're hungry, eat charcoal! [...] I am your prisoner and you will remain my wardens till the end\".{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=54-55}} After his bicycle was fixed, he rode away and finished the stage, 3 hours and 50 minutes later than the stage winner Thys. Christophe's chances to win the 1913 Tour de France were over.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913_6.php|title=6\u00e8me \u00e9tape - Bayonne-Luchon|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|language=French|accessdate=12 May 2009| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114250/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913_6.php| archive-date= 3 May 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter that sixth stage, [[Marcel Buysse]] was in the lead. In the ninth stage, Buysse had mechanical failure with a broken handlebar, and finished almost three and a half hours after stage winner Lambot. This was the end of the chances for Buysse for the victory.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/> Buysse did not give up, and won four of the remaining five stages.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=18\u201319}}\n\nThe lead had transferred to Thys now. In the last stages, the race focussed on the duel between Petit-Breton and Thys. In the 14th stage, Petit-Breton fell down and stopped the race. In the same stage, Thys also fell down and remained unconscious for a while. When he was conscious again, he was helped to repair his bicycle. All help was illegal in 1913, but the jury only gave him a 10-minute penalty.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/> Thys finished the stage, and kept 8'37\" in front of [[Gustave Garrigou]] in the general classification. In the final stage, Thys stayed with Garrigou, and so won the 1913 Tour de France.\n\n==Results==\n\n===Stage winners===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1913\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=11\u00e8me Tour de France 1913 |language=French |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvxmOFf?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913.php |archive-date=14 May 2009  |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=15}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1913 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvyBJvB?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archive-date=14 May 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1913, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 June || [[Paris]] to [[Le Havre]]\n| {{convert|388|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Giovanni Micheletto]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Giovanni Micheletto]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 1 July || [[Le Havre]] to [[Cherbourg]]\n| {{convert|364|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Jules Masselis]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Jules Masselis]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint|After the second stage, Masselis, Lauwers, Buysse and Defraye joint the lead. There were no rules for equal times in 1913.<ref name=\"veloarchive1913\"/>}}<br/ >{{flagathlete|[[Alfons Lauwers]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint}}<br/ >{{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint}}<br/ >{{flagathlete|[[Odile Defraye]]|BEL}}{{efn|name=joint}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 July || [[Cherbourg]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|405|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Pelissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Odile Defraye]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 July || [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[La Rochelle]]\n| {{convert|470|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Odile Defraye]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 July || [[La Rochelle]] to [[Bayonne]]\n| {{convert|379|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Van Lerberghe]]|BEL}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Odile Defraye]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July || [[Bayonne]] to [[Luchon]]\n| {{convert|326|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July || [[Luchon]] to [[Perpignan]]\n| {{convert|324|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July || [[Perpignan]] to [[Aix-en-Provence]]\n| {{convert|325|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage||  {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July || [[Aix-en-Provence]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|356|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July || [[Nice]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|333|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Francois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Geneva]]\n| {{convert|325|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July || [[Geneva]] to [[Belfort]]\n| {{convert|335|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July || [[Belfort]] to [[Longwy]]\n| {{convert|325|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25 July || [[Longwy]] to [[Dunkerque]]\n| {{convert|393|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 27 July || [[Dunkerque]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|340|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|5287|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\n[[File:Philippethys.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Philippe Thys]], the winner of the 1913 Tour de France.|alt=A man sitting on a bicycle]]\nFor each cyclist, the times they had needed in each stage was added up for the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]]. The cyclist with the least accumulated time after the last stage was the winner. Of the 140 starting cyclists, 25 finished.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:38em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Philippe Thys]]|BEL}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 197h 54' 00\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]]  || style=\"text-align:right;\" |  +8' 37\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Buysse]]|BEL}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]]  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 3h 30' 55\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Firmin Lambot]]|BEL}} || Griffon || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 4h 12' 45\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 6h 26' 04\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Alfons Spiessens]]|BEL}} || J.B. Louvet  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 7h 57' 52\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 14h 06' 35\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Camillo Bertarelli]]|ITA|1861}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 16h 21' 38\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Joseph Vandaele]]|BEL}} || J.B. Louvet || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 16h 39' 53\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Engel]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]]  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 16h 52' 34\"\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable noprint\" style=\"width:38em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Final general classification (11\u201325)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Sponsor!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || J.B. Louvet  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 18h 11' 13\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jules Deloffre]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 18h 31' 31\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n| {{flagathlete|[[Clemente Canepari]]|ITA|1861}} || J.B. Louvet  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 19h 11' 13\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Paul Deman (cyclist)|Paul Deman]]|BEL}} || Automoto || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 19h 27' 02\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 15\n| {{flagathlete|[[Vincent Dhulst]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 20h 10' 12\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 16\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Petitjean]]|BEL}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 22h 00' 27\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 17\n| {{flagathlete|[[Paul Hostein]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]]  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 25h 41' 06\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 18\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Leliaert]]|BEL}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 26h 18' 25\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 19\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Alavoine]]|FRA}} || [[Peugeot (cycling team)|Peugeot]]  || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 27h 43' 47\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 20\n| {{flagathlete|[[Giuseppe Contesini]]|ITA|1861}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 30h 37' 34\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 21\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Coolsaet]]|BEL}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 31h 46' 50\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 22\n| {{flagathlete|[[Achille De Smet]]|BEL}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 54h 44' 07\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 23\n| {{flagathlete|[[Charles Dumont (cyclist)|Charles Dumont]]|SUI}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 64h 33' 55\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 24\n| {{flagathlete|[[Celidonio Morini]]|ITA|1861}}|| \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 76h 31' 47\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 25\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Alavoine]]|FRA}} || \u2014 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 76h 55' 52\"\n|}\nIn the points system that had been used in previous years in the Tour de France, [[Gustave Garrigou|Garrigou]] would have won the race with 45 points, followed by Buysse with 48 points; Thys would have been third with 57 points.<ref name=\"elm\">{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1913/07/31/pagina-3/608360/pdf.html|title=La Vuelta a Francia|language=Spanish|date=31 July 1913|accessdate=19 December 2015|publisher=EL Mundo Deportivo}}</ref>\n\n===Other classifications===\n[[File:27-7-13 Tour de France Bertarelli.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Camillo Bertarelli]], the winner of the \"isol\u00e9s\" category, for cyclists not part of a team]]\n[[Camillo Bertarelli]], ranked 8 in the general classification, became the winner of the \"isol\u00e9s\" category.<ref name=\"letourfr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1913/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour - Ann\u00e9e 1913|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=8 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103034204/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1913/histoire.html|archive-date=3 January 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The \"isol\u00e9s\" classification was calculated in the same way as the general classification, but only the isolated cyclists (not part of a team) were eligible.\n\nThe organising newspaper l'Auto named Philippe Thys the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cossins|first1=Peter|last2=Best|first2=Isabel|last3=Sidwells|first3=Chris|last4=Griffith|first4=Clare|title=Le Tour 100: The Definitive History of the World's Greatest Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-eRYAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-84403-759-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Tour de France 1913|1913 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1913 Tour de France|1|8|9|15}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1913 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1913 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1913 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1913 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:June 1913 sports events|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1913 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1913 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1913 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1913 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1913 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after fifteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 29 June \u2013 27 July\n| stages             = 15\n| distance           = 5287\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 197h 54' 00\"\n| first              = [[Philippe Thys]]\n| first_nat          = BEL\n| first_team         = Peugeot\n| second             = [[Gustave Garrigou]]\n| second_nat         = FRA\n| second_team        = Peugeot\n| third              = [[Marcel Buysse]]\n| third_nat          = BEL\n| third_team         = Peugeot\n| previous           = [[1912 Tour de France|1912]]\n| next               = [[1914 Tour de France|1914]]\n}}\nThe '''1913 Tour de France''' was the 11th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place between 29 June and 27 July. The total distance was {{convert|5287|km|mi}} and the average speed of the riders was {{convert|26.715|km/h|mph}}.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} The competition was won by the [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[Philippe Thys]], after in the crucial sixth stage [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]] broke his bicycle and lost several hours because he had to do the repairs by himself. In the last stage, Thys also had mechanical problems, but he got help during the repairs, and only got a penalty of ten minutes.\n\nBetween 1904 and 1912, the overall classification had been calculated by points, but in 1913 the classification was reverted to the original format from 1903, where the overall classification was calculated by adding up the times of the individual stages. The general classification has been calculated in the time format ever since.\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nIn 1905, the format of the Tour de France had been changed from the time system to the points system, to reduce the cheating that had caused the first four cyclists of the 1904 Tour de France to be disqualified. In the 1912 Tour de France, this system had been working against [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]]'s chances, who would have been leading the time classification up until the final stage where he allowed a group to ride away.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1912.php |title=1912: Belgian victory foreshadows problems to come |publisher=VeloArchive |author=Tom James |date=14 August 2003 |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvybhFd?url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1912.php |archive-date=14 May 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> The system had been working against a French cyclist and in favor of a Belgian cyclist ([[Odiel Defraye]], who won the Tour de France in 1912), and the French organisation changed the system back again to the time system: the finishing times of all stages were added per cyclist, and the cyclist with the least total time was the winner. This was also intended to increase combativity, because in the points system riders did not care about time gaps, so escaped low-ranked riders were ignored by high-ranked cyclists.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|p=38}}\n\nFor the first time, the route of the race was in the opposite direction. Prior to the 1913 race, the Tour the France always had been in the clockwise direction through France, and in 1913 it was anticlockwise.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1913 Tour de France}}\n\nThe 1913 Tour started with 140 cyclists; there were 51 cyclists distributed over 9 teams, including all favourites for the overall victory. The remaining 89 cyclists started in the isol\u00e9s category.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/> This edition started with six former Tour de France winners ([[Louis Trousselier]], [[Lucien Petit-Breton]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], [[Octave Lapize]], [[Gustave Garrigou]] and [[Odile Defraye]]), the most ever.<ref name=\"veloarchive1913\"/>\n\nAlthough cyclists had started in teams previously, the rules had forbidden them to work together against other cyclists. In 1913, this changed, and cyclists from the same team were allowed to work together. The organisers preferred riders to ride solo, so they added a rule that if a cyclist would win a stage with a margin of 20 minutes or more, he would not only get his own prize money, but also the half of all the other cyclists' prize money of that stage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.historischekranten.be/issue/DPO/1913-06-29/edition/null/page/2?query=%22ronde%20van%20frankrijk%22&period=1903-1939&sort=issuedate%20ascending|title=De ronde van Frankrijk|language=Dutch|date=29 June 1913|accessdate=20 May 2014|work=De Poperinghenaar}}</ref>\n\nThe first African cyclist took part in the Tour de France in 1913: [[Ali Neffati]] from Tunisia. Neffati had been discovered by Tour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]], and would later become a driver at ''[[l'Auto]]'', the newspaper that organised the Tour de France.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8|1913 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15}}\n\n[[File:27-7-13 Tour de France Thys.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Philippe Thys]], winner of the 1913 Tour de France, after finishing the race]]\nIn the first stages, not much happened in the overall classification, as most cyclists were saving their energy for the Pyrenees.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=18\u201319}} The stage was won by Italian [[Giovanni Micheletto]] in a sprint. Micheletto was not part of the first group in the second stage, and thus lost his lead. There were four cyclists who had been in the lead group in both stages, and they were jointly leading the Tour.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=1&mod=krantresultaat&q=masselis&datering=7/1913&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=datum+asc%2Ckrant+asc%2Cpagina+asc&paragraaf=70&doc=6&p=3&paragraaf=96&y=376|title=De algemeene klassering na de twee eerste ritten|language=Dutch|date=3 July 1913|accessdate=20 October 2013|publisher=Documentatiecentrum en Archief voor Daensisme en Hedendaagse Geschiedenis van de Denderstreek|work=De Volksstem|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022063042/http://aalst.courant.nu/index.php?page=1&mod=krantresultaat&q=masselis&datering=7%2F1913&qt=paragraaf&pagina=&sort=datum+asc%2Ckrant+asc%2Cpagina+asc&paragraaf=70&doc=6&p=3&paragraaf=96&y=376|archive-date=22 October 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe most important event occurred in the third stage, when former winner Lapize stopped the race; either because he considered his earning insufficient,<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1913/histoire.html |title=1913 - 11th Tour de France |publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation|ASO]] |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvzQdR4?url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1913/us/annee.html |archive-date=14 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> or because he thought his team was not good enough.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|p=38}}\n\nThe crucial stage proved to be the sixth. At the start of the sixth stage, last year's winner Defraye lead the general classification, some 5 minutes ahead of [[Eug\u00e8ne Christophe]].{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|p=38}} In that sixth stage, the first mountains were climbed. Defraye was dropped quickly, and Christophe lead the race.<ref name=\"veloarchive1913\"/> Christophe came up first on the Aubisque, and in second place behind [[Philippe Thys]] on the [[Tourmalet]]. On the way down from the Tourmalet, Christophe was hit by a race vehicle,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2007/jan/07/cycling.features|title=There's unlucky ... and then there's Christophe|first=Matt|last=Rendell|date=7 January 2007|accessdate=17 December 2015|publisher=[[theguardian.com]]}}</ref> and his fork broke, rendering his bike unusable, and the rules said that he had to repair it himself. He walked more than 10&nbsp;km down to the next village, and found a place where he could repair his bicycle. He worked on it for over three hours, being watched by race officials who made sure that he was not helped by anyone. When Christophe asked a small boy, of seven years old, to work the [[bellows]], he was fined with ten minutes.<ref name=\"veloarchive1913\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1913.php|title=1913: Eug\u00e8ne Christophe, Ste. Marie de Campan and the forge|author=Tom James|publisher=VeloArchive|date=14 August 2003| accessdate= 12 May 2009}}</ref><ref>Strack, F. (February 2019). Power to the people?: The rise of the e-bike causes Frank Strack to consider the essence of what it means to be a cyclist. ''Cyclist:The Thrill of the Ride'', (83), 48.</ref> During this repair, angry with the draconian rules, he snapped: (at the hungry race commissaires) \"If you're hungry, eat charcoal! [...] I am your prisoner and you will remain my wardens till the end\".{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=54-55}} After his bicycle was fixed, he rode away and finished the stage, 3 hours and 50 minutes later than the stage winner Thys. Christophe's chances to win the 1913 Tour de France were over.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913_6.php|title=6\u00e8me \u00e9tape - Bayonne-Luchon|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|language=French|accessdate=12 May 2009| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090503114250/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913_6.php| archive-date= 3 May 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAfter that sixth stage, [[Marcel Buysse]] was in the lead. In the ninth stage, Buysse had mechanical failure with a broken handlebar, and finished almost three and a half hours after stage winner Lambot. This was the end of the chances for Buysse for the victory.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/> Buysse did not give up, and won four of the remaining five stages.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=18\u201319}}\n\nThe lead had transferred to Thys now. In the last stages, the race focussed on the duel between Petit-Breton and Thys. In the 14th stage, Petit-Breton fell down and stopped the race. In the same stage, Thys also fell down and remained unconscious for a while. When he was conscious again, he was helped to repair his bicycle. All help was illegal in 1913, but the jury only gave him a 10-minute penalty.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/> Thys finished the stage, and kept 8'37\" in front of [[Gustave Garrigou]] in the general classification. In the final stage, Thys stayed with Garrigou, and so won the 1913 Tour de France.\n\n==Results==\n\n===Stage winners===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1913\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=11\u00e8me Tour de France 1913 |language=French |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvxmOFf?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1913.php |archive-date=14 May 2009  |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=15}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1913 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |accessdate=12 May 2009 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5glvyBJvB?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archive-date=14 May 2009 |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1913, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1913\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1913 Tour de France, Stage 1 