{"title_page": "International Imaging Industry Association", "text_new": "[[File:International Imaging Industry Association Logo.jpg|thumb|200px|Logo of the International Imaging Industry Association]]\n\nThe '''International Imaging Industry Association''' ('''I3A''') was created by a merger of the [[Photographic and Imaging Manufacturers Association]] (PIMA) and the [[Digital Imaging Group]] in 2001. It was a common forum for the industrial imaging industry.\n\nIt used to supervise standards for photography and digital imaging, such as [[JPEG 2000]], [[Picture Transfer Protocol|PTP]], and [[Internet Imaging Protocol]].\n\nIt disbanded in October 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/preservation/digital/formats/fdd/fdd000241.shtml|title=Camera Raw Formats (Group Description)|date=2016-12-15|website=www.loc.gov|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==PIMA==\nThe Photographic and Imaging Manufacturers Association, or PIMA, was founded in 1946 under the name National Association of Photographic Manufacturers (NAPM). In 1997 the name was changed to PIMA.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.i3a.org/}} (defunct since 2013)\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20121023105031/http://www.i3a.org/ Archive]\n\n[[Category:Photography organizations]]\n[[Category:International trade associations|Imaging]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n\n\n{{business-org-stub}}\n{{photo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:International Imaging Industry Association Logo.jpg|thumb|200px|Logo of the International Imaging Industry Association]]\n\nThe '''International Imaging Industry Association''' ('''I3A''') was created by a merger of the [[Photographic and Imaging Manufacturers Association]] (PIMA) and the [[Digital Imaging Group]] in 2001. It was a common forum for the industrial imaging industry.\n\nIt used to supervise standards for photography and digital imaging, such as [[JPEG 2000]], [[Picture Transfer Protocol|PTP]], and [[Internet Imaging Protocol]].\n\nIt disbanded in October 2013.<ref>https://www.loc.gov/preservation/digital/formats/fdd/fdd000241.shtml</ref>\n\n==PIMA==\nThe Photographic and Imaging Manufacturers Association, or PIMA, was founded in 1946 under the name National Association of Photographic Manufacturers (NAPM). In 1997 the name was changed to PIMA.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.i3a.org/}} (defunct since 2013)\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20121023105031/http://www.i3a.org/ Archive]\n\n[[Category:Photography organizations]]\n[[Category:International trade associations|Imaging]]\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n\n\n{{business-org-stub}}\n{{photo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sarah M Borg", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed raw URL", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Imaging_Industry_Association"}
{"title_page": "1910 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1910 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1910 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1910 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1910 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after fourteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 1\u201331 July\n| stages             = 15\n| distance           = 4734\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 63 points\n| first              = [[Octave Lapize]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]\n| second_nat         = LUX\n| third              = [[Gustave Garrigou]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1909 Tour de France|1909]]\n| next               = [[1911 Tour de France|1911]]\n}}\nThe '''1910 Tour de France''' was the eighth edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place 3 to 31 July. It consisted of 15 stages over {{convert|4734|km|mi}}, ridden at an average speed of 28.680&nbsp;km/h.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} It was the first Tour to enter the [[Pyrenees]] mountains. Two main candidates for the victory were 1909 winner [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], a sprinter, and [[Octave Lapize]], a climber, both members of the powerful [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon team]]. Because of the points system, their chances for the overall victory were approximately equal. The race was not decided until the final stage, after which Lapize had won by a difference of only four points.\n\n==Innovations and changes==\nThe courses of the Tour de France in 1907, 1908 and 1909 had been nearly identical. In 1910, the [[Pyrenees]] were included, an initiative from [[Adolphe Stein\u00e8s]], who had drawn the course for the Tour de France since the first Tour in 1903.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} Compared to the 1907, 1908 and 1909 Tours, the stages N\u00eemes-Toulouse and Toulouse-Bayonne were replaced by three stages, N\u00eemes\u2013Perpignan, Perpignan\u2013Luchon and Luchon\u2013Bayonne.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\nTour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] at first refused the inclusion of the Pyrenees,{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}} but later gave in and sent Stein\u00e8s to the Pyrenees to see if it was possible to send cyclists up the mountains. Stein\u00e8s encountered many difficulties. He went there at 27 January 1910, and asked an innkeeper for directions over the Tourmalet. The innkeeper replied that it is barely crossable in July, so practically impossible in January. Stein\u00e8s hired a car anyway and rode up the mountain. Close to the top, there was so much snow that the car could not go further, and he continued on foot. Stein\u00e8s walked during the night, and fell down a ravine.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}} At 3 a.m. he was found by a search party. He quickly got some food and a hot bath.<ref name=\"reveal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/Feb06/top25-10.htm |title=Top 25 All Time Tours: 1910: \"Assassins...\" |publisher=Cycling revealed |date=February 2006 |accessdate=15 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi7ekim?url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/Feb06/top25-10.htm |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next morning, he sent a positive telegram to Desgrange: \"Have crossed the Tourmalet on foot STOP Road passable to vehicles STOP No snow STOP\".<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1910.php |first=Tom |last=James |date=14 August 2003 |accessdate=15 April 2009 |title=1910: The \"Assassins\" send the race to the Pyrenees |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi838xO?url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1910.php |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhen it was announced that the Pyrenees were included in the race, 136 cyclists had entered the race. After the news, 26 cyclists removed themselves from the starting list.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden\\tourlegendes\\De-angst-voor-de-Pyrenee\u00ebn-739.html |language=Dutch |title=De angst voor de Pyrenee\u00ebn |publisher=Tourdefrance.nl |accessdate=9 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018022805/http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden%5Ctourlegendes%5CDe-angst-voor-de-Pyrenee%C3%ABn-739.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 }}</ref> Other newspapers reacted to the Tour's route as \"dangerous\" and \"bizarre\".<ref name=\"reveal\"/>\n\nAlso new in 1910 was the broom wagon, to pick up the cyclists that abandoned during the race.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/> This was a reaction of the Tour organisers to the criticism of the cyclists, many cycling independently with no team support,{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}} on the difficult mountains.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}} It was designed to prevent riders from cheating, by using other forms of transport.{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}} In the tenth stage, over the four mountains in the Pyrenees, cyclists were allowed to finish the stage in the broom wagon and still start the next stage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}}{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}}\n\nTechnically, a new addition were gears. [[Lucien Petit-Breton]], [[Maurice Brocco]], [[Henri Cornet]], [[Charles Pavese]] and [[Jean Alavoine]] rode with gears.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\nWhat had not changed was the points system. A cyclist received points, based on their rankings. As in 1909, the points system was \"cleaned up\" two times: after the 9th stage and after the 14th stage. Cyclists who had abandoned the race were removed from the rankings of the previous stages, and the classification was recalculated.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1910 Tour de France}}\n\nAlthough cyclist were in 1909 able to register for the Tour with a sponsor, they were still considered to be riding as individuals; in 1910 they competed for the first time in teams.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}}\n\nThe cyclists were not so enthusiastic about the inclusion of the Pyren\u00e9es, and there were less participants: 110 instead of 150 in 1909.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} There were three teams with 10 cyclists each, including all the favourites for the overall victory: [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]], Le Globe and Legnano. The French team \"La Fran\u00e7aise\" decided not to join, but allowed their cyclists to ride for the Italian Legnano team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.historischekranten.be/issue/DPO/1910-06-26/edition/null/page/6?query=%22ronde%20van%20frankrijk%22&period=1903-1939&sort=issuedate%20ascending|title=De Ronde van Frankrijk - 5000 km, 25.000 fr prijzen|language=Dutch|date=26 June 1910|accessdate=20 May 2014|work=De Poperinghenaar}}</ref> The other 80 cyclists rode as individuals, this was called the \"isol\u00e9s\" category.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8|1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15}}\n\n[[File:Parc des Princes, 31-7-1910, Lapize \u00e0 son arriv\u00e9e du Tour de France.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Octave Lapize]] after winning the Tour at the [[Parc des Princes]] in Paris]]\nThe first stage, from Paris to [[Roubaix]], was won by [[Charles Crupelandt]]. In the second stage, [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]] showed his strengths, and won the stage, and took the lead.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}}\n\nOn the rest day between the sixth and seventh stage in Nice, cyclist [[Adolphe H\u00e9li\u00e8re]] died whilst swimming. He was the first victim of the Tour de France.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\nIn the ninth stage, four mountains were climbed, and Desgrange saw how much trouble the cyclists had on these mountains. The tenth stage would include the Pyrenees mountains, so Desgrange left the race and made Victor Breyer the director of the stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/2010/TDF/COURSE/us/les_pyrenees.html|title=The Tour and the Pyrenees: a love affair embarked upon one hundred years ago.|publisher=Amaury Sport Organisation|accessdate=9 February 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125130825/http://www.letour.fr/2010/TDF/COURSE/us/les_pyrenees.html|archivedate=25 January 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In that tenth stage, the Tourmalet was climbed, the highest point of the 1910 Tour de France. Octave Lapize reached the top first, followed by Gustave Garrigou. Garrigou was the only cyclist who reached the top without dismounting, and received an extra prize of 100 francs for that.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/> The next climb was the [[Aubisque]]. Lapize struggled there, and regional rider [[Fran\u00e7ois Lafourcade]] lead the race. The organisers had a car standing in top, and when Lafourcade passed them, they did not recognize him, and when they found out it was Lafourcade, they were surprised that such an unknown rider had been able to pass all the 'cracks'.{{sfn|Mulholland|2003|p=}} When Lapize passed the organiser's car (15 minutes later),{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}} he screamed \"Assassins!\",<ref name=\"letour\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1910/histoire.html |publisher=ASO |accessdate=15 April 2009 |title=1910 - 8th Tour de France |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi8SSao?url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1910/us/annee.html?RaceYear=1910&x=58&y=10 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and announced that he would give up during the descent.{{sfn|Mulholland|2003|p=}} Downhill, he refound his strength and was able to catch up to Lafourcade, and even win the stage.<ref name=\"letour\"/> By the end of the stage, ten riders had officially completed the stage on bike.{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}}\n\nAfter the 12th stage, Faber was leading the race by only one point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910_12.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=8\u00e8me Tour de France 1910, 12\u00e8m \u00e9tape|language=French|accessdate=9 April 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090503112734/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910_12.php| archivedate= 3 May 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In that stage to Brest, Faber punctured,{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} and Lapize took over the lead, helped by Garrigou.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}}\n\nIn the 14th stage, Faber sped away almost from the start in what could be his last chance to win the Tour de France. It seemed that he had a chance, until a flat tyre caused him to lose time, and Lapize could get back to him, again aided by Garrigou.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} Lapize improved his lead by winning the stage, and had a six-point margin before the last stage.\nIn that last stage, it was Lapize who suffered from a flat tyre, shortly after the start.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} Faber raced away, but could not pull off the stunt: he had a flat tyre.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} He still finished ahead of Lapize, but won back only two points, so the 1910 Tour de France was won by Lapize.\n\n==Results==\nThe [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon team]] was dominant in the 1910 Tour de France, winning 9 out of 15 stages.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\n===Stage results===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1910\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=8\u00e8me Tour de France 1910 |language=French |accessdate=9 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi6o8QE?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910.php |archivedate=4 May 2009  |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=12}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1910 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |first=Arian |last=Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi7EQbk?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=15 April 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1910, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 July || [[Paris]] to [[Roubaix]]\n| {{convert|269|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Charles Crupelandt]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Charles Crupelandt]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 July || [[Roubaix]] to [[Metz]]\n| {{convert|398|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 July || [[Metz]] to [[Belfort]]\n| {{convert|259|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July || [[Belfort]] to [[Lyon]]\n| {{convert|309|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July || [[Lyon]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|311|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Maitron]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July || [[Nice]] to [[N\u00eemes]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July || [[N\u00eemes]] to [[Perpignan]]\n| {{convert|216|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Paulmier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July || [[Perpignan]] to [[Luchon]]\n| {{convert|289|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July || [[Luchon]] to [[Bayonne]]\n| {{convert|326|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July || [[Bayonne]] to [[Bordeaux]]\n| {{convert|269|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ernest Paul]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25 July || [[Bordeaux]] to [[Nantes]]\n| {{convert|391|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 27 July || [[Nantes]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|321|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 July || [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Caen]]\n| {{convert|424|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 31 July || [[Caen]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|262|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ernesto Azzini]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4734|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\n[[File:Tour de France 1910 01 Octave Lapize.jpg|thumb|right|[[Octave Lapize]], the winner of the 1910 Tour de France, climbing the [[Tourmalet]] on foot.|alt=A man walking uphill, alongside his bicycle, followed by a car.]]\nOf the 110 starting cyclists, 41 finished. The winner, [[Octave Lapize]], received 5000 francs for his victory.<ref name=\"letour\"/> In total, he earned 7525 francs during the race; the average daily wages were around 5 to 7 francs.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=152}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:38em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 63\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 67\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 86\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Cyrille van Hauwaert]]|BEL}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 97\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Charles Cruchon]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 119\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Charles Crupelandt]]|FRA}} || Le Globe || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 148\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ernest Paul]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 154\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Blaise]]|BEL}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 166\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Maitron]]|FRA}} || Le Globe || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 171\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Aldo Bettini]]|ITA|1861}} || [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]] || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 175\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable noprint\" style=\"width:38em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Final general classification (11\u201341)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Sponsor!! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Albini]]|ITA|1861}} || Legnano || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 176\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 12\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Paulmier]]|FRA}} || Le Globe || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 182\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 13\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ernesto Azzini]]|ITA|1861}} || Legnano || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 194\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 14\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Lafourcade]]|FRA}} || Legnano || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 205\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 15\n| {{flagathlete|[[Henri Cornet]]|FRA}} || Le Globe || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 215\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 16\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jules Deloffre]]|FRA}} || Le Globe || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 216\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 17\n| {{flagathlete|[[Constant M\u00e9nager]]|FRA}} || Legnano || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 219\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 18\n| {{flagathlete|[[Luigi Azzini]]|ITA|1861}} || Legnano || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 220\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 19\n| {{flagathlete|[[Augustin Ringeval]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 243\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 20\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Saillot]]|FRA}} || Le Globe || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 257\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 21\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Pardon]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 316\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 22\n| {{flagathlete|[[Joseph Leblanc]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 346\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 23\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Fleury]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 357\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 24\n| {{flagathlete|[[Joseph Habierre]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 381\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 25\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Riou]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 398\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 26\n| {{flagathlete|[[Auguste Guyon]]|SUI}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 402\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 27\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jean Bouillet]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 406\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 28\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Pothier]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 410\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 29\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice Decaup]]|FRA}} || Legnano || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 428\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 30\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Leman]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 433\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 31\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gabriel Mathonat]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 443\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 32\n| {{flagathlete|[[Robert Chopard]]|SUI}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 447\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 33\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pietro Ghislotti]]|ITA|1861}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 592\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 34\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Rocquebert]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 502\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 35\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Cauvry]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 510\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 36\n| {{flagathlete|[[Camille Bi\u00e8re]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 519\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 37\n| {{flagathlete|[[Auguste Dufour]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 525\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 38\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Jouin (cyclist)|Louis Jouin]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 532\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 39\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Chaud\u00e9]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 549\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 40\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Picard]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 568\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 41\n| {{flagathlete|[[Constant Collet]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 580\n|}\n\n===Other classifications===\nFifth-placed Charles Cruchon became the winner of the \"isol\u00e9s\" category.<ref name=\"letourfr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1910/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour - Ann\u00e9e 1910|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=4 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716170725/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1910/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe organising newspaper l'Auto named [[Octave Lapize]] the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cossins|first1=Peter|last2=Best|first2=Isabel|last3=Sidwells|first3=Chris|last4=Griffith|first4=Clare|title=Le Tour 100: The Definitive History of the World's Greatest Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-eRYAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-84403-759-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Mulholland|first=Owen|title=Cycling's Great Climbers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cTTtPAAACAAJ|location=Boulder, CO|publisher=VeloPress|year=2003|isbn=978-1-931382-12-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2006|isbn=978-0-520-24760-4|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1910|1910 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1910 Tour de France|1|8|9|15}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1910 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1910 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1910 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1910 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1910 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1910 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1910 map-fr.svg\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1910 Tour de France followed clockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = Map of France with the route of the 1910 Tour de France on it, showing that the race started in Paris, went clockwise through France and ended in Paris after fourteen stages.\n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 1\u201331 July\n| stages             = 15\n| distance           = 4734\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 63 points\n| first              = [[Octave Lapize]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| second             = [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]\n| second_nat         = LUX\n| third              = [[Gustave Garrigou]]\n| third_nat          = FRA\n| previous           = [[1909 Tour de France|1909]]\n| next               = [[1911 Tour de France|1911]]\n}}\nThe '''1910 Tour de France''' was the eighth edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place 3 to 31 July. It consisted of 15 stages over {{convert|4734|km|mi}}, ridden at an average speed of 28.680&nbsp;km/h.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}} It was the first Tour to enter the [[Pyrenees]] mountains. Two main candidates for the victory were 1909 winner [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]], a sprinter, and [[Octave Lapize]], a climber, both members of the powerful [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon team]]. Because of the points system, their chances for the overall victory were approximately equal. The race was not decided until the final stage, after which Lapize had won by a difference of only four points.\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nThe courses of the Tour de France in 1907, 1908 and 1909 had been nearly identical. In 1910, the [[Pyrenees]] were included, an initiative from [[Adolphe Stein\u00e8s]], who had drawn the course for the Tour de France since the first Tour in 1903.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} Compared to the 1907, 1908 and 1909 Tours, the stages N\u00eemes-Toulouse and Toulouse-Bayonne were replaced by three stages, N\u00eemes\u2013Perpignan, Perpignan\u2013Luchon and Luchon\u2013Bayonne.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\nTour organiser [[Henri Desgrange]] at first refused the inclusion of the Pyrenees,{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}} but later gave in and sent Stein\u00e8s to the Pyrenees to see if it was possible to send cyclists up the mountains. Stein\u00e8s encountered many difficulties. He went there at 27 January 1910, and asked an innkeeper for directions over the Tourmalet. The innkeeper replied that it is barely crossable in July, so practically impossible in January. Stein\u00e8s hired a car anyway and rode up the mountain. Close to the top, there was so much snow that the car could not go further, and he continued on foot. Stein\u00e8s walked during the night, and fell down a ravine.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}} At 3 a.m. he was found by a search party. He quickly got some food and a hot bath.<ref name=\"reveal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/Feb06/top25-10.htm |title=Top 25 All Time Tours: 1910: \"Assassins...\" |publisher=Cycling revealed |date=February 2006 |accessdate=15 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi7ekim?url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/Feb06/top25-10.htm |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> The next morning, he sent a positive telegram to Desgrange: \"Have crossed the Tourmalet on foot STOP Road passable to vehicles STOP No snow STOP\".<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1910.php |first=Tom |last=James |date=14 August 2003 |accessdate=15 April 2009 |title=1910: The \"Assassins\" send the race to the Pyrenees |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi838xO?url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1910.php |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nWhen it was announced that the Pyrenees were included in the race, 136 cyclists had entered the race. After the news, 26 cyclists removed themselves from the starting list.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden\\tourlegendes\\De-angst-voor-de-Pyrenee\u00ebn-739.html |language=Dutch |title=De angst voor de Pyrenee\u00ebn |publisher=Tourdefrance.nl |accessdate=9 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121018022805/http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden%5Ctourlegendes%5CDe-angst-voor-de-Pyrenee%C3%ABn-739.html |archivedate=18 October 2012 }}</ref> Other newspapers reacted to the Tour's route as \"dangerous\" and \"bizarre\".<ref name=\"reveal\"/>\n\nAlso new in 1910 was the broom wagon, to pick up the cyclists that abandoned during the race.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/> This was a reaction of the Tour organisers to the criticism of the cyclists, many cycling independently with no team support,{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}} on the difficult mountains.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}} It was designed to prevent riders from cheating, by using other forms of transport.{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}} In the tenth stage, over the four mountains in the Pyrenees, cyclists were allowed to finish the stage in the broom wagon and still start the next stage.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=640\u2013646}}{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}}\n\nTechnically, a new addition were gears. [[Lucien Petit-Breton]], [[Maurice Brocco]], [[Henri Cornet]], [[Charles Pavese]] and [[Jean Alavoine]] rode with gears.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\nWhat had not changed was the points system. A cyclist received points, based on their rankings. As in 1909, the points system was \"cleaned up\" two times: after the 9th stage and after the 14th stage. Cyclists who had abandoned the race were removed from the rankings of the previous stages, and the classification was recalculated.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1910 Tour de France}}\n\nAlthough cyclist were in 1909 able to register for the Tour with a sponsor, they were still considered to be riding as individuals; in 1910 they competed for the first time in teams.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=36}}\n\nThe cyclists were not so enthusiastic about the inclusion of the Pyren\u00e9es, and there were less participants: 110 instead of 150 in 1909.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} There were three teams with 10 cyclists each, including all the favourites for the overall victory: [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon]], Le Globe and Legnano. The French team \"La Fran\u00e7aise\" decided not to join, but allowed their cyclists to ride for the Italian Legnano team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.historischekranten.be/issue/DPO/1910-06-26/edition/null/page/6?query=%22ronde%20van%20frankrijk%22&period=1903-1939&sort=issuedate%20ascending|title=De Ronde van Frankrijk - 5000 km, 25.000 fr prijzen|language=Dutch|date=26 June 1910|accessdate=20 May 2014|work=De Poperinghenaar}}</ref> The other 80 cyclists rode as individuals, this was called the \"isol\u00e9s\" category.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\n==Race overview==\n\n{{main|1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8|1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15}}\n\n[[File:Parc des Princes, 31-7-1910, Lapize \u00e0 son arriv\u00e9e du Tour de France.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Octave Lapize]] after winning the Tour at the [[Parc des Princes]] in Paris]]\nThe first stage, from Paris to [[Roubaix]], was won by [[Charles Crupelandt]]. In the second stage, [[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]] showed his strengths, and won the stage, and took the lead.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}}\n\nOn the rest day between the sixth and seventh stage in Nice, cyclist [[Adolphe H\u00e9li\u00e8re]] died whilst swimming. He was the first victim of the Tour de France.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\nIn the ninth stage, four mountains were climbed, and Desgrange saw how much trouble the cyclists had on these mountains. The tenth stage would include the Pyrenees mountains, so Desgrange left the race and made Victor Breyer the director of the stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/2010/TDF/COURSE/us/les_pyrenees.html|title=The Tour and the Pyrenees: a love affair embarked upon one hundred years ago.|publisher=Amaury Sport Organisation|accessdate=9 February 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125130825/http://www.letour.fr/2010/TDF/COURSE/us/les_pyrenees.html|archivedate=25 January 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In that tenth stage, the Tourmalet was climbed, the highest point of the 1910 Tour de France. Octave Lapize reached the top first, followed by Gustave Garrigou. Garrigou was the only cyclist who reached the top without dismounting, and received an extra prize of 100 francs for that.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/> The next climb was the [[Aubisque]]. Lapize struggled there, and regional rider [[Fran\u00e7ois Lafourcade]] lead the race. The organisers had a car standing in top, and when Lafourcade passed them, they did not recognize him, and when they found out it was Lafourcade, they were surprised that such an unknown rider had been able to pass all the 'cracks'.{{sfn|Mulholland|2003|p=}} When Lapize passed the organiser's car (15 minutes later),{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}} he screamed \"Assassins!\",<ref name=\"letour\">{{cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1910/histoire.html |publisher=ASO |accessdate=15 April 2009 |title=1910 - 8th Tour de France |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi8SSao?url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/TDF/1910/us/annee.html?RaceYear=1910&x=58&y=10 |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and announced that he would give up during the descent.{{sfn|Mulholland|2003|p=}} Downhill, he refound his strength and was able to catch up to Lafourcade, and even win the stage.<ref name=\"letour\"/> By the end of the stage, ten riders had officially completed the stage on bike.{{sfn|Cossins|Best|Sidwells|Griffith|2013|pp=48\u201349}}\n\nAfter the 12th stage, Faber was leading the race by only one point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910_12.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=8\u00e8me Tour de France 1910, 12\u00e8m \u00e9tape|language=French|accessdate=9 April 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090503112734/http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910_12.php| archivedate= 3 May 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In that stage to Brest, Faber punctured,{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} and Lapize took over the lead, helped by Garrigou.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}}\n\nIn the 14th stage, Faber sped away almost from the start in what could be his last chance to win the Tour de France. It seemed that he had a chance, until a flat tyre caused him to lose time, and Lapize could get back to him, again aided by Garrigou.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} Lapize improved his lead by winning the stage, and had a six-point margin before the last stage.\nIn that last stage, it was Lapize who suffered from a flat tyre, shortly after the start.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} Faber raced away, but could not pull off the stunt: he had a flat tyre.{{sfn|Amels|1984|pp=15\u201316}} He still finished ahead of Lapize, but won back only two points, so the 1910 Tour de France was won by Lapize.\n\n==Results==\nThe [[Alcyon (cycling team)|Alcyon team]] was dominant in the 1910 Tour de France, winning 9 out of 15 stages.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>\n\n===Stage results===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1910\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=8\u00e8me Tour de France 1910 |language=French |accessdate=9 April 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi6o8QE?url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1910.php |archivedate=4 May 2009  |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=12}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1910 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |first=Arian |last=Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWi7EQbk?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=15 April 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type{{efn|In 1910, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.<ref name=\"mdc1910\"/>}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 3 July || [[Paris]] to [[Roubaix]]\n| {{convert|269|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Charles Crupelandt]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Charles Crupelandt]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 5 July || [[Roubaix]] to [[Metz]]\n| {{convert|398|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 7 July || [[Metz]] to [[Belfort]]\n| {{convert|259|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Emile Georget]]|FRA}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9 July || [[Belfort]] to [[Lyon]]\n| {{convert|309|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 11 July || [[Lyon]] to [[Grenoble]]\n| {{convert|311|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 13 July || [[Grenoble]] to [[Nice]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Maitron]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 15 July || [[Nice]] to [[N\u00eemes]]\n| {{convert|345|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 8#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17 July || [[N\u00eemes]] to [[Perpignan]]\n| {{convert|216|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Paulmier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 19 July || [[Perpignan]] to [[Luchon]]\n| {{convert|289|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 21 July || [[Luchon]] to [[Bayonne]]\n| {{convert|326|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s)|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 23 July || [[Bayonne]] to [[Bordeaux]]\n| {{convert|269|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ernest Paul]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 25 July || [[Bordeaux]] to [[Nantes]]\n| {{convert|391|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Trousselier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Fran\u00e7ois Faber]]|LUX}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 27 July || [[Nantes]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]]\n| {{convert|321|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Gustave Garrigou]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 29 July || [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Caen]]\n| {{convert|424|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1910 Tour de France, Stage 9 to Stage 15#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 31 July || [[Caen]] to [[Paris]]\n| {{convert|262|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage|| {{flagathlete|[[Ernesto Azzini]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Octave Lapize]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4734|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n===General classification===\n[[File:Tour de France 1910 01 Octave Lapize.jpg|thumb|right|[[Octave Lapize]], the winner of the 1910 Tour de France, climbing the [[Tourmalet]] on foot.|alt=A man walking uphill, alongside his bicycle, followed by a car.]]\nOf the 110 starting cyclists, 41 finished. The winner, [[Octave Lapize]], received 5000 francs for his victory.<ref name=\"letour\"/> In total, he earned 7525 francs during the race; the average daily wages were around 5 to 7 francs.{{sfn|Thompson|2006|p=152}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:38em; margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)