athlete|[[Lucien Leman]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 433\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 31\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gabriel Mathonat]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 443\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 32\n| {{flagathlete|[[Robert Chopard]]|SUI}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 447\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 33\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pietro Ghislotti]]|ITA|1861}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 592\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 34\n| {{flagathlete|[[Lucien Rocquebert]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 502\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 35\n| {{flagathlete|[[Georges Cauvry]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 510\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 36\n| {{flagathlete|[[Camille Bi\u00e8re]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 519\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 37\n| {{flagathlete|[[Auguste Dufour]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 525\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 38\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Jouin (cyclist)|Louis Jouin]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 532\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 39\n| {{flagathlete|[[Ren\u00e9 Chaud\u00e9]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 549\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 40\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Picard]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 568\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | 41\n| {{flagathlete|[[Constant Collet]]|FRA}} || \u2013 || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 580\n|}\n\n===Other classifications===\nFifth-placed Charles Cruchon became the winner of the \"isol\u00e9s\" category.<ref name=\"letourfr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1910/histoire.html|title=l'Historique du Tour - Ann\u00e9e 1910|language=French|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=4 January 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716170725/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/fr/TDF/1910/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2010|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nThe organising newspaper l'Auto named [[Octave Lapize]] the ''meilleur grimpeur''. This unofficial title is the precursor to the [[mountains classification in the Tour de France|mountains classification]].{{sfn|Cleijne|2014|p=156}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Amels|first=Wim|title=De geschiedenis van de Tour de France 1903\u20131984|location=Valkenswaard, Netherlands|publisher=Sport-Express|year=1984|language=Dutch|isbn=978-90-70763-05-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jacques|last=Augendre|author-link=Jacques Augendre|url=http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|title=Guide historique|trans-title=Historical guide|year=2016|language=French|access-date=27 October 2016|format=PDF|work=[[Tour de France]]|location=Paris|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cleijne|first=Jan|title=Legends of the Tour|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3nCNAwAAQBAJ|year=2014|location=London|publisher=Head of Zeus|isbn=978-1-78185-998-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Cossins|first1=Peter|last2=Best|first2=Isabel|last3=Sidwells|first3=Chris|last4=Griffith|first4=Clare|title=Le Tour 100: The Definitive History of the World's Greatest Race|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-eRYAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=[[Hachette UK]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-84403-759-9|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Mulholland|first=Owen|title=Cycling's Great Climbers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cTTtPAAACAAJ|location=Boulder, CO|publisher=VeloPress|year=2003|isbn=978-1-931382-12-0}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Christopher S.|title=The Tour de France: A Cultural History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M-vUF6Y_4RUC|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|location=Oakland, CA|year=2006|isbn=978-0-520-24760-4|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Tour de France 1910|1910 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1910 Tour de France|1|8|9|15}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1910 Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1910 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1910 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year]]\n[[Category:1910 in road cycling|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:July 1910 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInnovations and changes:Changes from the previous Tour \u2192 Innovations and changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1910_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "Operation Retribution (1941)", "text_new": "{{featured article}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Operation Retribution\n| partof      = the [[Invasion of Yugoslavia]]\n| image       = Image:Bundesarchiv Bild 141-1005, Belgrad, Zerst\u00f6rungen.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| caption     = Bomb-damaged buildings in Belgrade in April 1941\n| alt = a damaged building and damaged tram\n| date        = 6\u20137/8 April 1941\n| place       = [[Belgrade]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|44|49|N|20|28|E|display=INLINE,title}}\n| map_type    =\n| map_relief  =\n| latitude    =\n| longitude   =\n| map_size    =\n| map_marksize =\n| map_caption =\n| map_label   =\n| territory   =\n| result      = {{plainlist|\n* Paralysis of Yugoslav command and control\n* Widespread destruction and civilian casualties\n }}\n| status      =\n| combatants_header =\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Nazi Germany|name=Germany}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Kingdom of Yugoslavia|name=Yugoslavia}}\n| combatant3  =\n| commander1  =\n| commander2  =\n| commander3  =\n| units1      = [[Luftflotte 4|''Luftflotte'' IV]]<br/>[[8th Air Corps (Germany)|''Fliegerkorps'' VIII]]\n| units2      = [[Royal Yugoslav Army Air Force]]\n| units3      =\n| strength1   =\n| strength2   =\n| strength3   =\n| casualties1 =\n| casualties2 =\n| casualties3 = see [[Operation Retribution (1941)#Aftermath and legacy|Aftermath]] section\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Invasion of Yugoslavia}}\n}}\n\n'''Operation Retribution''' ({{lang-de|Unternehmen Strafgericht}}), also known as '''Operation Punishment''',{{refn|The military historian Christopher Chant states that the codename was ''Unternehmen Bestrafung'' (Operation Punishment).{{sfn|Chant|1986|p=17}} [[Martin Gilbert]], a historian specialising in the [[Holocaust]], writes that the operation was codenamed ''[[wikt:castigo|Castigo]]'' (\"punishment\").{{sfn|Gilbert|1989|p=170}} The historian Vladimir Terzi\u0107 offers the [[Serbo-Croatian]] translation, ''Kazna'' (\"punishment\").{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=283}}|group=lower-alpha}} was the April 1941 [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Strategic bombing|bombing]] of [[Belgrade]], the capital of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], in retaliation for the [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] that overthrew the government that had signed the [[Tripartite Pact]]. The bombing occurred in the first days of the German-led [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia]] during [[World War II]]. The [[Royal Yugoslav Army Air Force]] (VVKJ) had only 77 modern [[fighter aircraft]] available to defend Belgrade against the hundreds of German fighters and [[bomber]]s that struck in the first wave early on 6 April. Three days prior, VVKJ [[Major]] [[Vladimir Kren]] had defected to the Germans, disclosing the locations of multiple military assets and divulging the VVKJ's codes.\n\nThree more waves of bombers attacked Belgrade on 6 April, and more attacks followed in subsequent days. The attacks resulted in the paralysis of Yugoslav civilian and military command and control, the widespread destruction of Belgrade's infrastructure, and many civilian casualties. The bombing of Belgrade was preceded by the commencement of the ground invasion a few hours earlier, and coincided with air attacks on VVKJ airfields and other strategic targets across Yugoslavia. Among the non-military targets struck during the bombing were the [[National Library of Serbia]], which burned to the ground with the loss of hundreds of thousands of books and manuscripts, and the [[Belgrade Zoo]].\n\nThe [[Royal Air Force]] carried out two bombing raids on [[Sofia]], the capital of [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], in retaliation for the attacks on Yugoslavia, which ultimately surrendered on 17 April. The senior [[Luftwaffe]] officer responsible for the bombing, ''[[Generaloberst]]'' [[Alexander L\u00f6hr]], was captured by the Yugoslavs at the end of the war and was tried and executed for war crimes, in part for his involvement in the bombing of Belgrade. Kren was arrested in 1947 on unrelated charges of war crimes stemming from his subsequent service as the head of the [[Air Force of the Independent State of Croatia]]. He was extradited to Yugoslavia to face trial, found guilty on all counts and executed in 1948. A monument erected in [[New Belgrade]] in 1997 commemorates the Yugoslav airmen who were killed in Belgrade's defense. The bombing has been dramatised in literature and film.\n\n==Background==\n===Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat===\n{{main|Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|Tripartite Pact}}\nFollowing [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]'s 1938 ''[[Anschluss]]'' of [[First Austrian Republic|Austria]], Yugoslavia shared a border with the Third Reich and came under increasing pro-[[Axis powers|Axis]] political pressure as her neighbours fell into line with the Axis powers. In April 1939, Yugoslavia gained a second frontier with [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] when that country [[Italian invasion of Albania|invaded Albania]]. Between September and November 1940, [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346)|Hungary]] joined the [[Tripartite Pact]], Italy [[Greco-Italian War|invaded Greece]], and [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]] also joined the Pact.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|pp=6\u20137}} From that time, Yugoslavia was almost surrounded by Axis powers or their [[client state]]s, and her neutral stance toward the war was under tremendous pressure. On 14 February 1941, [[Adolf Hitler]] invited Prime Minister [[Dragi\u0161a Cvetkovi\u0107]] and Foreign Minister [[Aleksandar Cincar-Markovi\u0107]] to [[Berchtesgaden]], and requested that Yugoslavia also join the Pact.{{sfn|Presseisen|1960|p=367}} On 1 March, [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] joined, and the next day, German troops entered Bulgaria from Romania, closing the ring around Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=12}}\n\nFurther pressure was applied by Hitler on 4 March 1941, when the Yugoslav regent, Prince [[Prince Paul of Yugoslavia|Paul]], visited Berchtesgaden, but the prince delayed a decision.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=12}} On 6 March, the [[Royal Yugoslav Army Air Force]] ({{lang-sh|Vazduhoplovstvo Vojske Kraljevine Jugoslavije}}, VVKJ) was secretly mobilised.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} The following day, British troops began landing in Greece to bolster the country's defences against the Italians.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=13}} On 12 March, the VVKJ began dispersing to auxiliary airfields. By 20 March, the VVKJ's dispersal had been completed.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} Hitler, wishing to secure his southern flank in anticipation of Germany's impending [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]], demanded that Yugoslavia sign the Pact. On 25 March, the Yugoslav government [[Yugoslav accession to the Tripartite Pact|complied]].{{sfn|Milazzo|1975|p=2}} Two days later, a group of VVKJ and Yugoslav [[Royal Guard]] officers, led by [[Brigadier General]] [[Borivoje Mirkovi\u0107]], deposed Prince Paul in a [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|pp=43\u201344}} He was replaced by his 17-year-old nephew [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter]], who was declared to be of age to accede to the throne.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=47}}\n\n===Preparations===\n{{main|Yugoslav order of battle prior to the invasion of Yugoslavia}}\nThe day of the coup, Hitler issued [[Adolf Hitler's directives|Directive 25]], which stated that the coup had changed the political situation in the [[Balkans]]. He ordered that \"even if Yugoslavia at first should give declarations of loyalty, she must be considered as a foe and therefore must be destroyed as quickly as possible\".{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=15}} German reconnaissance aircraft frequently violated Yugoslav airspace in the aftermath of the coup. VVKJ [[fighter aircraft|fighters]] were placed on constant alert. The German incursions demonstrated that the Yugoslav ground observation post network and supporting radio communications were inadequate.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} Hitler decided that [[Belgrade]] would be bombed as punishment for the coup, under the codename Operation Retribution (''Unternehmen Strafgericht''). On 27 and 28 March 1941, ''[[Reichsmarschall]]'' [[Hermann G\u00f6ring]] transferred about 500 fighter and bomber aircraft from France and northern Germany to airfields near the Yugoslav border. The commander of [[Luftflotte 4|''Luftflotte'' IV]], ''[[Generaloberst]]'' (General) [[Alexander L\u00f6hr]], allocated these aircraft to attack the Yugoslav capital in waves by day and night. L\u00f6hr issued his orders for the bombing on 31 March, but the decision to bomb Belgrade would not be confirmed by Hitler until 5 April.{{sfn|Schreiber|Stegemann|Vogel|1995|p=497}} Although Hitler ordered the general destruction of Belgrade, at the last minute L\u00f6hr replaced these general directions with specific military objectives within the city.{{sfn|Boog|Krebs|Vogel|2006|p=366}}\n\nOn 3 April, [[Major]] [[Vladimir Kren]] defected to the Germans, flying a [[Potez 25]] aircraft to [[Graz]] in Austria, and disclosed the locations of many of Yugoslavia's dispersal airfields, as well as codes used by the VVKJ, which had to be quickly changed.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} Also disclosed were the location of Yugoslavia's troop mobilisation centres and air-raid shelters in Belgrade.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}} On the afternoon of 5 April, a British [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] visited Mirkovi\u0107 at the VVKJ base in [[Zemun]] and informed him that the attack on Belgrade would commence at 06:30 the following morning.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} The previous day, the Yugoslav government had declared Belgrade an [[open city]] in the event of hostilities. Although the German embassy had informed its government that Belgrade did not contain any [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft defences]], in an effort to justify the attack to the public, German propaganda branded the city \"Fortress Belgrade\" after the first bombs were dropped.{{sfn|Schreiber|Stegemann|Vogel|1995|p=497}}\n\nBy 6 April, the VVKJ had been almost completely mobilised, and consisted of four air brigades with more than 423 aircraft of Yugoslav, German, Italian, French, Czech and British design, including 107 modern fighters and 100 modern [[medium bomber]]s. Other than a small number of locally made [[Rogo\u017earski IK-3]] fighters, almost all the modern aircraft available to the VVKJ were of German, Italian or British design for which limited spares and munitions were available.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=173}} The available aircraft were spread all over the country, and only the 1st Fighter Brigade was near enough to Belgrade to respond to an attack on the capital. In total, the 1st Fighter Brigade fielded 56 [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]E-3a fighters, 15 [[Hawker Hurricane]] MkIs, and six Rogo\u017earski IK-3s.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=187\u2013188}}\n\n==Bombing==\n{{also|Invasion of Yugoslavia}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F016226-0005A, Belgrad, Altes Schloss, Sch\u00e4den.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The bomb-damaged [[Stari dvor|Old Palace]] in central Belgrade, struck during the first wave of bombing on 6 April 1941.|alt=Trucks travelling along wide tree-lined street with large old building in the background]]\nGerman ground forces crossed the Yugoslav border at 05:15 on 6 April, and the [[Ministry of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda|Reich Minister of Propaganda]], ''[[Reichsleiter]]'' [[Joseph Goebbels]], announced Germany's declaration of war at 06:00.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=179}} The invasion and concurrent bombing coincided with [[Easter]] Sunday as observed by the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]], which uses the [[Julian calendar]].{{sfn|Zaki\u0107|2017|p=64}} Yugoslav anti-aircraft defences caused a false alarm when they reported the approach of an air raid from the direction of Romania at 03:00, but listening posts on the Romanian border had actually heard the aircraft engines of the Romanian-based ''Fliegerf\u00fchrer'' Arad warming up well before they took off. The VVKJ's 51st Fighter Group at Zemun had been alerted before dawn, and when reports began to be received about Luftwaffe attacks on VVKJ airfields, the first patrol was sent into the air. At first, no aircraft could be seen approaching Belgrade.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=196}}\n\nThe first wave closed on Belgrade between 06:30 and 06:45, and consisted of 74 [[Junkers Ju 87]] ''Stuka'' dive bombers, and 160 [[Heinkel He 111]] medium bombers and [[Dornier Do 17]] [[light bomber]]s at {{convert|8000|-|10000|ft|m}}. They were escorted by [[Messerschmitt Bf 110]] [[heavy fighter]]s at {{convert|11000|-|12000|ft|m}} and 100 Messerschmitt Bf 109E fighters at {{convert|15000|ft|m}}.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=283}}{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=195}} The entire Yugoslav 6th Fighter Brigade, consisting of the 51st Fighter Group at Zemun and the 32nd Fighter Group at [[Prnjavor (Belgrade)#Boroughs|Prnjavor]], totalling 29 Messerschmitt Bf 109Es and five Rogo\u017earski IK-3s, were scrambled to intercept the Germans.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=196\u2013197}} The Yugoslavs were quickly engaged by escorting Messerschmitt Bf 109Es from [[Jagdgeschwader 77|''Jagdgeschwader'' 77]] (JG 77). Just as the first wave was departing, Hawker Hurricane Mk1s of the 52nd Fighter Group of the 2nd Fighter Regiment based at [[Kni\u0107]] arrived over Belgrade and engaged some dive bombers, claiming one ''Stuka'' shot down. During the first attack, the Yugoslavs claimed fifteen German aircraft shot down and lost five of their own, with six more badly damaged. The pilots of JG 77 claimed ten Yugoslav machines shot down and another six destroyed on the ground.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=196\u2013198}} On his return to base, the commander of the 51st Fighter Group was relieved of his command for failure to take action.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}} The first wave hit the Belgrade power station, the [[General Post Office, Belgrade|post office]] including telegraph and postal services, the headquarters of the Ministry of Army and Navy, the [[Supreme Command (Kingdom of Yugoslavia)|Yugoslav Supreme Command]] building, the [[Military Academy (Serbia)|military academy]], the [[Royal Compound, Belgrade|royal palace at Dedinje]], the royal guard barracks at [[Top\u010dider]], the gendarmerie command headquarters, and the airport at Zemun, among other targets.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}}\n\nImmediately after the first wave, King Peter, the Government of Yugoslavia and the Yugoslav Supreme Command left Belgrade and retreated to Yugoslavia's mountainous interior with the intention of going into exile.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=50}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=17}} The second wave of German aircraft arrived over Belgrade about 10:00, consisting of 57 Ju 87 dive bombers and 30 Bf 109E fighters. They were met by 15 of the remaining fighters from the 6th Fighter Brigade. This time the Yugoslavs claimed two dive bombers forced down, and one Bf 109E shot down. A patrol of Bf 109Es from the Yugoslav 31st Fighter Group based at [[Kragujevac]], acting without orders from their group commander, followed the Germans as they returned to their bases and claimed two dive bombers shot down for the loss of both Yugoslav aircraft.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}}\n[[File:Bombed National Library Belgrad.JPG|thumb|250px|left|A 2008 photograph of the ruins of the National Library of Serbia, bombed on 6 April 1941|alt=an overgrown crater with ruined walls around part of the perimeter]]\nBelgrade was targeted on two other occasions on the first day of the invasion. The third wave struck at 14:00, consisting of 94 twin-engined bombers flying from airfields near [[Vienna]], escorted by 60 fighters. This wave was met by eighteen fighters of the 6th Fighter Regiment, which claimed four German aircraft. The fourth attack of the day approached Belgrade at 16:00, comprising 97 dive bombers and 60 fighters.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}}\n\nThe Germans claimed nineteen Yugoslav Bf 109E fighters and four unidentified aircraft destroyed on 6 April. Actual Yugoslav aircraft losses on the first day were ten shot down and fifteen damaged. The Yugoslavs claimed to have shot down twenty-two German aircraft and forced two others to land. The Germans lost twelve aircraft, significantly fewer than claimed by the Yugoslavs: two Do 17Z light bombers, five Bf 110 heavy fighters, four Ju 87 dive bombers, and one Bf 109E fighter.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}} One Luftwaffe pilot who claimed his first victory over Belgrade on 6 April was ''[[Oberleutnant]]'' [[Gerhard Koall]] of [[Jagdgeschwader 54|''Jagdgeschwader'' 54]].{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}} He went on to be credited with 37 victories and was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] in 1944.{{sfn|Fellgiebel|2000|p=216}}\n\nGerman bombers and dive-bombers dropped {{convert|215|-|360|LT|ST}} of [[aerial bomb|bombs]] and [[Incendiary device|incendiaries]] on the capital.{{sfn|Zajac|1993|p=31}}{{sfn|Knell|2009|p=194}} The weak VVKJ and inadequate anti-aircraft defences of Belgrade briefly attempted to meet the overwhelming Luftwaffe assault, but were eliminated as threats during the first wave of the attack. Sources vary regarding the success achieved by the defenders. A US Army study first published in 1953 states that the Luftwaffe lost two fighter aircraft, downed 20 Yugoslav aircraft and destroyed a further 44 on the ground.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p=49}} The military historian Daniel L. Zajac writes that the Germans lost 40 aircraft during the two-day air battle.{{sfn|Zajac|1993|p=31}} Another source indicates the loss of 14 German aircraft on 6 April.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=200\u2013208}} Dive-bombers in subsequent waves were able to operate at rooftop altitude.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p=49}}\n\nAccording to the historian [[Stevan K. Pavlowitch]], the bombing of Belgrade lasted three days.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=17}} Other sources state the air battle over Belgrade lasted only two days owing to poor flying conditions on 8 April.{{sfn|Zajac|1993|p=31}} The most important cultural institution that was destroyed was the [[National Library of Serbia]], which was hit by bombs and gutted by fire. Hundreds of thousands of rare books, maps, and [[medieval]] manuscripts were destroyed.{{sfn|Norris|2008|p=41}} Also struck was the [[Belgrade Zoo]], sending frightened animals running through the streets.{{sfn|Freeman|2008|p=94}}\n\n==British retaliation==\n[[No. 37 Squadron RAF|No. 37 Squadron]] of the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) conducted two bombing raids on [[Sofia]], the capital of Bulgaria, in retaliation for the bombing of Belgrade. Operating [[Vickers Wellington]] bombers from an airfield in [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]], the squadron conducted raids on 6/7 April and 12/13 April, dropping a total of {{convert|30|LT|ST}} of high-explosive bombs on railway targets and nearby residential areas. These raids were carried out despite the fact that Britain was not at war with Bulgaria until 12 December 1941. The historian Herman Knell calls the retaliatory justification for these raids \"strange and implausible\".{{sfn|Knell|2009|p=195}} The aviation historians Shores, Cull and Malizia indicate that these raids were attacks on the lines of communication of German forces attacking Greece and Yugoslavia, and note that the raid on 6/7 April targeted an ammunition train and other installations in Sofia, and the raid on 12/13 April bombed the railway marshalling yards. Other similar targets in Bulgaria were attacked by the RAF during the [[Balkans Campaign (World War II)|Balkans Campaign]].{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=232, 243}}\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\n[[File:Spomenik pilotima 1941.JPG|thumb|200px|Monument to the Yugoslav pilots killed during Operation Retribution, located in [[New Belgrade]]|alt=rectangular polished dark stone plinth pointing toward the sky, with a winged plaque and inscription at the base]]\nThe bombing of Belgrade paralyzed communications between the Yugoslav military and its headquarters, and contributed decisively to the rapid collapse of Yugoslav resistance.{{sfn|Boog|Krebs|Vogel|2006|p=366}} Civilian casualties were significant, but sources vary widely from 1,500 to 17,000 killed.{{sfn|Knell|2009|pp=194\u2013195}} They were worsened by the disclosure of air-raid shelter locations to the Germans in the days preceding the attack.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}} The official casualty figure released by the occupation authorities soon after the bombing was 2,271 killed. Other sources mention 5,000 to 10,000 fatalities, and later Yugoslav estimates ranged even higher.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=16}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=18}} The historian [[Jozo Tomasevich]] writes that the higher estimates were downgraded following \"careful postwar investigations\", and indicates that a figure between 3,000 and 4,000 is more realistic.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=74}}\n\nBelgrade was occupied on 13 April 1941, and four days later, Yugoslavia capitulated.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=19}} Afterwards, Luftwaffe engineers conducted a bomb damage assessment in Belgrade. The report stated that {{convert|218.5|MT}} of bombs were dropped, 10 to 14 percent being incendiaries. It listed all the targets of the bombing, mentioned that seven aerial mines were dropped, and that areas in the centre and northwest of the city had been destroyed, comprising 20 to 25 percent of its total area. Some aspects of the bombing remain unexplained, particularly the use of the aerial mines.{{sfn|Boog|Krebs|Vogel|2006|p=366}} Significant damage was done to Belgrade, particularly to the water and electrical systems.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}} Pavlowitch states that almost 50 percent of housing in Belgrade was destroyed.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=17\u201318}} After the invasion, the Germans forced between 3,500 and 4,000 [[Jews]] to collect rubble that was caused by the bombing.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=131}} Unexploded German bombs continue to be unearthed in the 21st century.{{sfn|Nikolic 28 July 2015}}\n\nL\u00f6hr was captured by the [[Yugoslav Partisans]] on 9 May 1945, escaped, and was recaptured on 13 May. He was intensively interrogated, after which he was tried before a Yugoslav military court on war crimes charges, one of which related to his command of ''Luftflotte'' IV during Operation Retribution. L\u00f6hr was convicted by the Yugoslav military court and sentenced to death.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=756\u2013757}} He was executed on 26 February 1947.{{sfn|Barbier|2017|p=155}} Following the invasion, Kren was appointed head of the [[Air Force of the Independent State of Croatia]] ({{lang-hr|Zrakoplovstvo Nezavisne Dr\u017eave Hrvatske}}, ZNDH). He was arrested in Italy in March 1947 and extradited to Yugoslavia, where he was tried on unrelated charges of war crimes for his role in the targeting of civilians by the ZNDH. He was found guilty on all counts and executed in 1948.{{sfn|Go\u00f1i|2002|p=236}}\n\nThe bombing of Belgrade was depicted in the 1980 Yugoslav feature film ''[[Who's Singin' Over There?]]'' ({{lang-sh|Ko to tamo peva|link=no}}) and the 1995 feature film ''[[Underground (1995 film)|Underground]]'' ({{lang-sh|Podzemlje|link=no}}).{{sfn|Goulding|2002|pp=167\u2013168, 186}} It is also the subject of [[Miodrag Pavlovi\u0107]]'s poem ''Belgrade 1941'' ({{lang-sh|Beograd 1941|link=no}}).{{sfn|Norris|2008|p=124}} The [[Serbian American]] poet [[Charles Simic]], a survivor of the bombing, wrote a poem titled ''Cameo Appearance'' recounting his experiences.{{sfn|Forhan|2008|pp=255\u2013256}} A monument commemorating the Yugoslav pilots killed during Operation Retribution was inaugurated in [[New Belgrade]] on 6 April 1997. It was designed by the sculptor [[Miodrag \u017divkovi\u0107 (sculptor)|Miodrag \u017divkovi\u0107]].{{sfn|Glas javnosti 29 July 2005}} On 6 April 2016, the 75th anniversary of the bombing, a memorial service was held for the victims, attended by the Serbian [[Ministry of Labour, Employment, Veteran and Social Policy (Serbia)|Minister for Labour, Employment, Veteran and Social Policy]], [[Aleksandar Vulin]].{{sfn|B92 6 April 2016}} In June 2017, it was announced that the site containing the ruined foundations of the National Library of Serbia would be transformed into a memorial garden.{{sfn|Radio Television of Serbia 25 June 2017}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n\n'''Books'''\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Barbier\n  | first = Mary Kathryn\n  | year = 2017\n  | title = Spies, Lies, and Citizenship: The Hunt for Nazi Criminals\n  | publisher = University of Nebraska Press\n  | location = Lincoln, Nebraska\n  | isbn = 978-1-61234-973-2\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=IK8yDwAAQBAJ\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Boog\n  | first1 = Horst\n  | authorlink1 = Horst Boog\n  | last2 = Krebs\n  | first2 = Gerhard\n  | last3 = Vogel\n  | first3 = Detlef\n  | authorlink3 = Detlef Vogel\n  | year = 2006\n  | title = Germany and the Second World War: Volume VII: The Strategic Air War in Europe and the War in the West and East Asia, 1943\u20131944/5\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | location = Oxford, England\n  | isbn = 978-1-280-75877-5\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rVVeO4B985wC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Chant\n  | first = Christopher\n  | year = 1986\n  | title = The Encyclopedia of Codenames of World War II\n  | publisher = Routledge\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-415-71087-9\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Fellgiebel\n  | first = Walther-Peer\n  | authorlink = Walther-Peer Fellgiebel\n  | year = 2000\n  | title = Die Tr\u00e4ger des Ritterkreuzes des Eisernen Kreuzes 1939\u20131945 \u2013 Die Inhaber der h\u00f6chsten Auszeichnung des Zweiten Weltkrieges aller Wehrmachtsteile\n  |trans-title = The Bearers of the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross 1939\u20131945 \u2013 The Owners of the Highest Award of the Second World War of all Wehrmacht Branches\n  | language = German\n  | publisher = Podzun-Pallas\n  | location = Friedberg, Germany\n  | isbn = 978-3-7909-0284-6\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Freeman\n  | first = Gregory A.\n  | year = 2008\n  | title = The Forgotten 500: The Untold Story of the Men Who Risked All for the Greatest Rescue Mission of World War II\n  | publisher = Penguin Books\n  | location = New York\n  | isbn = 978-0-451-22495-8\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=zkZJ6yHG-xwC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | author-last = Forhan\n  | author-first = Chris\n  | editor1-last= Tobin\n  | editor1-first = Daniel\n  | editor2-last = Triplett\n  | editor2-first = Pimone\n  | year = 2008\n  | title = Poet's Work, Poet's Play: Essays on the Practice and the Art\n  | chapter = When I Say \"I\": Poets' Use of the First Person\n  | publisher = University of Michigan Press\n  | location = Ann Arbor, Michigan\n  | isbn = 978-0-47206-997-2\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OcGSGpUzbwIC\n  | pages = 250\u2013265\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Gilbert\n  | first = Martin\n  | authorlink = Martin Gilbert\n  | year = 1989\n  | title = The Second World War: A Complete History\n  | edition = rev.\n  | publisher = Henry Holt and Co.\n  | location = New York\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Go\u00f1i\n  | first = Uki\n  | authorlink = Go\u00f1i\n  | year = 2002\n  | title = The Real Odessa: Smuggling the Nazis to Per\u00f3n's Argentina\n  | publisher = Granta Books\n  | location = New York, New York\n  | isbn = 978-1-86207-581-8\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Goulding\n  | first = Daniel J.\n  | year = 2002\n  | title = Liberated Cinema: The Yugoslav Experience, 1945\u20132001\n  | publisher = Indiana University Press\n  | location = Bloomington, Indiana\n  | isbn = 978-0-253-21582-6\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=z6KOL-DnxIkC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Knell\n  | first = Herman\n  | year = 2009\n  | title = To Destroy a City: Strategic Bombing and Its Human Consequences in World War II\n  | publisher = Da Capo Press\n  | location = Cambridge, Massachusetts\n  | isbn = 978-0-7867-4849-5\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=dwf57uOIU5kC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Milazzo\n  | first = Matteo J.\n  | year = 1975\n  | title = The Chetnik Movement & the Yugoslav Resistance\n  | publisher = Johns Hopkins University Press\n  | location = Baltimore, Maryland\n  | isbn = 978-0-8018-1589-8\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Norris\n  | first = David A.\n  | year = 2008\n  | title = Belgrade: A Cultural History\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | location = Oxford, England\n  | isbn = 978-0-19-970452-1\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=b7RWayXdH0UC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Pavlowitch\n  | first = Stevan K.\n  | authorlink = Stevan K. Pavlowitch\n  | year = 2007\n  | title = Hitler's New Disorder: The Second World War in Yugoslavia\n  | publisher = Columbia University Press\n  | location = New York\n  | isbn = 978-1-85065-895-5\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Ramet\n  | first = Sabrina P.\n  | authorlink = Sabrina P. Ramet\n  | year = 2006\n  | title = The Three Yugoslavias: State-Building and Legitimation, 1918\u20132005\n  | publisher = Indiana University Press\n  | location = Bloomington, Indiana\n  | isbn = 978-0-253-34656-8\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=FTw3lEqi2-oC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Roberts\n  | first = Walter R.\n  | authorlink = Walter Roberts (writer)\n  | year = 1973\n  | title = Tito, Mihailovi\u0107 and the Allies 1941\u20131945\n  | publisher = Duke University Press\n  | location = Durham, North Carolina\n  | isbn = 978-0-8223-0773-0\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=43CbLU8FgFsC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Schreiber\n  | first1 = Gerhard\n  | authorlink1 = Gerhard Schreiber\n  | last2 = Stegemann\n  | first2 = Bernd\n  | authorlink2 = Bernd Stegemann\n  | last3 = Vogel\n  | first3 = Detlef\n  | year = 1995\n  | title = Germany and the Second World War: Volume III: The Mediterranean, South-East Europe, and North Africa, 1939\u201341\n  | publisher = Clarendon Press\n  | location = Oxford, England\n  | isbn = 978-0-19-822884-4\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=GO3_aoOzTi4C\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Shores\n  | first1 = Christopher F.\n  | last2 = Cull\n  | first2 = Brian\n  | last3 = Malizia\n  | first3 = Nicola\n  | year = 1987\n  | title = Air War for Yugoslavia, Greece, and Crete, 1940\u201341\n  | publisher = Grub Street\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-948817-07-6\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Terzi\u0107\n  | first = Velimir\n  | year = 1982\n  | title = Slom Kraljevine Jugoslavije 1941: Uzroci i posledice poraza\n  |trans-title=The Collapse of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia in 1941: Causes and Consequences of Defeat\n  | language = Serbo-Croatian\n  | volume = 2\n  | publisher = Narodna knjiga\n  | location = Belgrade\n  | oclc = 10276738\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Tomasevich\n  | first = Jozo\n  | authorlink = Jozo Tomasevich\n  | year = 1975\n  | title = War and Revolution in Yugoslavia, 1941\u20131945: The Chetniks\n  | publisher = Stanford University Press\n  | location = Stanford, California\n  | isbn = 978-0-8047-0857-9\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Tomasevich\n  | first = Jozo\n  | year = 2001\n  | title = War and Revolution in Yugoslavia, 1941\u20131945: Occupation and Collaboration\n  | publisher = Stanford University Press\n  | location = Stanford, California\n  | isbn = 978-0-8047-3615-2\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=fqUSGevFe5MC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | author = U.S. Army\n  | year = 1986\n  | origyear = 1953\n  | title = The German Campaigns in the Balkans (Spring 1941)\n  | publisher = United States Army Center of Military History\n  | location = Washington, D.C.\n  | id = CMH Pub 104-4\n  | url = http://www.history.army.mil/books/wwii/balkan/intro.htm\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Zaki\u0107\n  | first = Mirna\n  | year = 2017\n  | title = Ethnic Germans and National Socialism in Yugoslavia in World War II\n  | publisher = Cambridge University Press\n  | location = Cambridge, England\n  | isbn = 978-1-10717-184-8\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=v1xEDgAAQBAJ\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Journals'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal\n  | last = Presseisen\n  | first = Ernst L.\n  | title = Prelude to \"Barbarossa\": Germany and the Balkans, 1940\u20131941\n  | journal = Journal of Modern History\n  |date=December 1960\n  | volume = 32\n  | issue = 4\n  | pages = 359\u2013370\n  | publisher = University of Chicago Press\n  | location = Chicago, Illinois\n  | jstor = 1872611\n  | ref = harv\n  | doi=10.1086/238616\n  }}\n{{refend}}\n\n'''News reports'''\n\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite news|publisher=B92|title=Belgrade marks anniversary of German WW2 bombing|url=https://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics.php?yyyy=2016&mm=04&dd=06&nav_id=97604|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=27 July 2018|ref={{harvid|B92 6 April 2016}}}}\n* {{cite news|publisher=Radio Television of Serbia|title=Na Kosan\u010di\u0107evom vencu bi\u0107e memorijalni park|language=Serbian|url=http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/sr/story/125/drustvo/2781636/na-kosancicevom-vencu-bice-memorijalni-park.html|date=25 June 2017|accessdate=21 July 2018|ref={{harvid|Radio Television of Serbia 25 June 2017}}}}\n* {{cite news|last=Nikolic|first=Ivana|publisher=Balkan Insight|title=Serbia's Deminers Harvest a Deadly Crop|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/serbia-s-deminers-harvest-a-deadly-crop|date=28 July 2015|accessdate=30 July 2018|ref={{harvid|Nikolic 28 July 2015}}}}\n* {{cite news|newspaper=Glas javnosti|title=Spomenik pilotima braniocima|language=Serbian|url=http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2005/07/29/srpski/BG05072807.shtml|date=29 July 2005|accessdate=21 July 2018|ref={{harvid|Glas javnosti 29 July 2005}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n'''Papers'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite thesis | last = Zajac | first = Daniel L. | title = The German Invasion of Yugoslavia: Insights For Crisis Action Planning And Operational Art in A Combined Environment | publisher = School of Advanced Military Studies, United States Army Command and General Staff College |location = Fort Leavenworth, Kansas | url = http://www.dtic.mil/docs/citations/ADA274043 | date = May 1993 | ref = harv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{WWII city bombing|state=collapsed}}\n{{Yugoslav Front}}\n{{World War II}}\n\n[[Category:1940s in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:1941 in Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Aerial operations and battles of World War II involving Germany]]\n[[Category:April 1941 events]]\n[[Category:Axis war crimes in Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1941]]\n[[Category:Military history of Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Nazi war crimes in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Yugoslavia in World War II]]\n", "text_old": "{{featured article}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Operation Retribution\n| partof      = the [[Invasion of Yugoslavia]]\n| image       = Image:Bundesarchiv Bild 141-1005, Belgrad, Zerst\u00f6rungen.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| caption     = Bomb-damaged buildings in Belgrade in April 1941\n| alt = a damaged building and damaged tram\n| date        = 6\u20137/8 April 1941\n| place       = [[Belgrade]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]\n|coordinates = {{Coord|44|49|N|20|28|E|display=INLINE,title}}\n| map_type    =\n| map_relief  =\n| latitude    =\n| longitude   =\n| map_size    =\n| map_marksize =\n| map_caption =\n| map_label   =\n| territory   =\n| result      = {{plainlist|\n* Paralysis of Yugoslav command and control\n* Widespread destruction and civilian casualties\n }}\n| status      =\n| combatants_header =\n| combatant1  = {{flag|Nazi Germany|name=Germany}}\n| combatant2  = {{flag|Kingdom of Yugoslavia|name=Yugoslavia}}\n| combatant3  =\n| commander1  =\n| commander2  =\n| commander3  =\n| units1      = [[Luftflotte 4|''Luftflotte'' IV]]<br>[[8th Air Corps (Germany)|''Fliegerkorps'' VIII]]\n| units2      = [[Royal Yugoslav Army Air Force]]\n| units3      =\n| strength1   =\n| strength2   =\n| strength3   =\n| casualties1 =\n| casualties2 =\n| casualties3 = see [[Operation Retribution (1941)#Aftermath and legacy|Aftermath]] section\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Invasion of Yugoslavia}}\n}}\n\n'''Operation Retribution''' ({{lang-de|Unternehmen Strafgericht}}), also known as '''Operation Punishment''',{{refn|The military historian Christopher Chant states that the codename was ''Unternehmen Bestrafung'' (Operation Punishment).{{sfn|Chant|1986|p=17}} [[Martin Gilbert]], a historian specialising in the [[Holocaust]], writes that the operation was codenamed ''[[wikt:castigo|Castigo]]'' (\"punishment\").{{sfn|Gilbert|1989|p=170}} The historian Vladimir Terzi\u0107 offers the [[Serbo-Croatian]] translation, ''Kazna'' (\"punishment\").{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=283}}|group=lower-alpha}} was the April 1941 [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Strategic bombing|bombing]] of [[Belgrade]], the capital of the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], in retaliation for the [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] that overthrew the government that had signed the [[Tripartite Pact]]. The bombing occurred in the first days of the German-led [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia]] during [[World War II]]. The [[Royal Yugoslav Army Air Force]] (VVKJ) had only 77 modern [[fighter aircraft]] available to defend Belgrade against the hundreds of German fighters and [[bomber]]s that struck in the first wave early on 6 April. Three days prior, VVKJ [[Major]] [[Vladimir Kren]] had defected to the Germans, disclosing the locations of multiple military assets and divulging the VVKJ's codes.\n\nThree more waves of bombers attacked Belgrade on 6 April, and more attacks followed in subsequent days. The attacks resulted in the paralysis of Yugoslav civilian and military command and control, the widespread destruction of Belgrade's infrastructure, and many civilian casualties. The bombing of Belgrade was preceded by the commencement of the ground invasion a few hours earlier, and coincided with air attacks on VVKJ airfields and other strategic targets across Yugoslavia. Among the non-military targets struck during the bombing were the [[National Library of Serbia]], which burned to the ground with the loss of hundreds of thousands of books and manuscripts, and the [[Belgrade Zoo]].\n\nThe [[Royal Air Force]] carried out two bombing raids on [[Sofia]], the capital of [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]], in retaliation for the attacks on Yugoslavia, which ultimately surrendered on 17 April. The senior [[Luftwaffe]] officer responsible for the bombing, ''[[Generaloberst]]'' [[Alexander L\u00f6hr]], was captured by the Yugoslavs at the end of the war and was tried and executed for war crimes, in part for his involvement in the bombing of Belgrade. Kren was arrested in 1947 on unrelated charges of war crimes stemming from his subsequent service as the head of the [[Air Force of the Independent State of Croatia]]. He was extradited to Yugoslavia to face trial, found guilty on all counts and executed in 1948. A monument erected in [[New Belgrade]] in 1997 commemorates the Yugoslav airmen who were killed in Belgrade's defense. The bombing has been dramatised in literature and film.\n\n==Background==\n===Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat===\n{{main|Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|Tripartite Pact}}\nFollowing [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]'s 1938 ''[[Anschluss]]'' of [[First Austrian Republic|Austria]], Yugoslavia shared a border with the Third Reich and came under increasing pro-[[Axis powers|Axis]] political pressure as her neighbours fell into line with the Axis powers. In April 1939, Yugoslavia gained a second frontier with [[Kingdom of Italy|Italy]] when that country [[Italian invasion of Albania|invaded Albania]]. Between September and November 1940, [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346)|Hungary]] joined the [[Tripartite Pact]], Italy [[Greco-Italian War|invaded Greece]], and [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]] also joined the Pact.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|pp=6\u20137}} From that time, Yugoslavia was almost surrounded by Axis powers or their [[client state]]s, and her neutral stance toward the war was under tremendous pressure. On 14 February 1941, [[Adolf Hitler]] invited Prime Minister [[Dragi\u0161a Cvetkovi\u0107]] and Foreign Minister [[Aleksandar Cincar-Markovi\u0107]] to [[Berchtesgaden]], and requested that Yugoslavia also join the Pact.{{sfn|Presseisen|1960|p=367}} On 1 March, [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] joined, and the next day, German troops entered Bulgaria from Romania, closing the ring around Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=12}}\n\nFurther pressure was applied by Hitler on 4 March 1941, when the Yugoslav regent, Prince [[Prince Paul of Yugoslavia|Paul]], visited Berchtesgaden, but the prince delayed a decision.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=12}} On 6 March, the [[Royal Yugoslav Army Air Force]] ({{lang-sh|Vazduhoplovstvo Vojske Kraljevine Jugoslavije}}, VVKJ) was secretly mobilised.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} The following day, British troops began landing in Greece to bolster the country's defences against the Italians.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=13}} On 12 March, the VVKJ began dispersing to auxiliary airfields. By 20 March, the VVKJ's dispersal had been completed.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} Hitler, wishing to secure his southern flank in anticipation of Germany's impending [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]], demanded that Yugoslavia sign the Pact. On 25 March, the Yugoslav government [[Yugoslav accession to the Tripartite Pact|complied]].{{sfn|Milazzo|1975|p=2}} Two days later, a group of VVKJ and Yugoslav [[Royal Guard]] officers, led by [[Brigadier General]] [[Borivoje Mirkovi\u0107]], deposed Prince Paul in a [[Yugoslav coup d'\u00e9tat|military coup d'\u00e9tat]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|pp=43\u201344}} He was replaced by his 17-year-old nephew [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter]], who was declared to be of age to accede to the throne.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=47}}\n\n===Preparations===\n{{main|Yugoslav order of battle prior to the invasion of Yugoslavia}}\nThe day of the coup, Hitler issued [[Adolf Hitler's directives|Directive 25]], which stated that the coup had changed the political situation in the [[Balkans]]. He ordered that \"even if Yugoslavia at first should give declarations of loyalty, she must be considered as a foe and therefore must be destroyed as quickly as possible\".{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=15}} German reconnaissance aircraft frequently violated Yugoslav airspace in the aftermath of the coup. VVKJ [[fighter aircraft|fighters]] were placed on constant alert. The German incursions demonstrated that the Yugoslav ground observation post network and supporting radio communications were inadequate.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} Hitler decided that [[Belgrade]] would be bombed as punishment for the coup, under the codename Operation Retribution (''Unternehmen Strafgericht''). On 27 and 28 March 1941, ''[[Reichsmarschall]]'' [[Hermann G\u00f6ring]] transferred about 500 fighter and bomber aircraft from France and northern Germany to airfields near the Yugoslav border. The commander of [[Luftflotte 4|''Luftflotte'' IV]], ''[[Generaloberst]]'' (General) [[Alexander L\u00f6hr]], allocated these aircraft to attack the Yugoslav capital in waves by day and night. L\u00f6hr issued his orders for the bombing on 31 March, but the decision to bomb Belgrade would not be confirmed by Hitler until 5 April.{{sfn|Schreiber|Stegemann|Vogel|1995|p=497}} Although Hitler ordered the general destruction of Belgrade, at the last minute L\u00f6hr replaced these general directions with specific military objectives within the city.{{sfn|Boog|Krebs|Vogel|2006|p=366}}\n\nOn 3 April, [[Major]] [[Vladimir Kren]] defected to the Germans, flying a [[Potez 25]] aircraft to [[Graz]] in Austria, and disclosed the locations of many of Yugoslavia's dispersal airfields, as well as codes used by the VVKJ, which had to be quickly changed.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} Also disclosed were the location of Yugoslavia's troop mobilisation centres and air-raid shelters in Belgrade.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}} On the afternoon of 5 April, a British [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|colonel]] visited Mirkovi\u0107 at the VVKJ base in [[Zemun]] and informed him that the attack on Belgrade would commence at 06:30 the following morning.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=177}} The previous day, the Yugoslav government had declared Belgrade an [[open city]] in the event of hostilities. Although the German embassy had informed its government that Belgrade did not contain any [[Anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft defences]], in an effort to justify the attack to the public, German propaganda branded the city \"Fortress Belgrade\" after the first bombs were dropped.{{sfn|Schreiber|Stegemann|Vogel|1995|p=497}}\n\nBy 6 April, the VVKJ had been almost completely mobilised, and consisted of four air brigades with more than 423 aircraft of Yugoslav, German, Italian, French, Czech and British design, including 107 modern fighters and 100 modern [[medium bomber]]s. Other than a small number of locally made [[Rogo\u017earski IK-3]] fighters, almost all the modern aircraft available to the VVKJ were of German, Italian or British design for which limited spares and munitions were available.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=173}} The available aircraft were spread all over the country, and only the 1st Fighter Brigade was near enough to Belgrade to respond to an attack on the capital. In total, the 1st Fighter Brigade fielded 56 [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]]E-3a fighters, 15 [[Hawker Hurricane]] MkIs, and six Rogo\u017earski IK-3s.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=187\u2013188}}\n\n==Bombing==\n{{also|Invasion of Yugoslavia}}\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F016226-0005A, Belgrad, Altes Schloss, Sch\u00e4den.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The bomb-damaged [[Stari dvor|Old Palace]] in central Belgrade, struck during the first wave of bombing on 6 April 1941.|alt=Trucks travelling along wide tree-lined street with large old building in the background]]\nGerman ground forces crossed the Yugoslav border at 05:15 on 6 April, and the [[Ministry of Public Enlightenment and Propaganda|Reich Minister of Propaganda]], ''[[Reichsleiter]]'' [[Joseph Goebbels]], announced Germany's declaration of war at 06:00.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=179}} The invasion and concurrent bombing coincided with [[Easter]] Sunday as observed by the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]], which uses the [[Julian calendar]].{{sfn|Zaki\u0107|2017|p=64}} Yugoslav anti-aircraft defences caused a false alarm when they reported the approach of an air raid from the direction of Romania at 03:00, but listening posts on the Romanian border had actually heard the aircraft engines of the Romanian-based ''Fliegerf\u00fchrer'' Arad warming up well before they took off. The VVKJ's 51st Fighter Group at Zemun had been alerted before dawn, and when reports began to be received about Luftwaffe attacks on VVKJ airfields, the first patrol was sent into the air. At first, no aircraft could be seen approaching Belgrade.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=196}}\n\nThe first wave closed on Belgrade between 06:30 and 06:45, and consisted of 74 [[Junkers Ju 87]] ''Stuka'' dive bombers, and 160 [[Heinkel He 111]] medium bombers and [[Dornier Do 17]] [[light bomber]]s at {{convert|8000|-|10000|ft|m}}. They were escorted by [[Messerschmitt Bf 110]] [[heavy fighter]]s at {{convert|11000|-|12000|ft|m}} and 100 Messerschmitt Bf 109E fighters at {{convert|15000|ft|m}}.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=283}}{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=195}} The entire Yugoslav 6th Fighter Brigade, consisting of the 51st Fighter Group at Zemun and the 32nd Fighter Group at [[Prnjavor (Belgrade)#Boroughs|Prnjavor]], totalling 29 Messerschmitt Bf 109Es and five Rogo\u017earski IK-3s, were scrambled to intercept the Germans.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=196\u2013197}} The Yugoslavs were quickly engaged by escorting Messerschmitt Bf 109Es from [[Jagdgeschwader 77|''Jagdgeschwader'' 77]] (JG 77). Just as the first wave was departing, Hawker Hurricane Mk1s of the 52nd Fighter Group of the 2nd Fighter Regiment based at [[Kni\u0107]] arrived over Belgrade and engaged some dive bombers, claiming one ''Stuka'' shot down. During the first attack, the Yugoslavs claimed fifteen German aircraft shot down and lost five of their own, with six more badly damaged. The pilots of JG 77 claimed ten Yugoslav machines shot down and another six destroyed on the ground.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=196\u2013198}} On his return to base, the commander of the 51st Fighter Group was relieved of his command for failure to take action.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}} The first wave hit the Belgrade power station, the [[General Post Office, Belgrade|post office]] including telegraph and postal services, the headquarters of the Ministry of Army and Navy, the [[Supreme Command (Kingdom of Yugoslavia)|Yugoslav Supreme Command]] building, the [[Military Academy (Serbia)|military academy]], the [[Royal Compound, Belgrade|royal palace at Dedinje]], the royal guard barracks at [[Top\u010dider]], the gendarmerie command headquarters, and the airport at Zemun, among other targets.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}}\n\nImmediately after the first wave, King Peter, the Government of Yugoslavia and the Yugoslav Supreme Command left Belgrade and retreated to Yugoslavia's mountainous interior with the intention of going into exile.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=50}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=17}} The second wave of German aircraft arrived over Belgrade about 10:00, consisting of 57 Ju 87 dive bombers and 30 Bf 109E fighters. They were met by 15 of the remaining fighters from the 6th Fighter Brigade. This time the Yugoslavs claimed two dive bombers forced down, and one Bf 109E shot down. A patrol of Bf 109Es from the Yugoslav 31st Fighter Group based at [[Kragujevac]], acting without orders from their group commander, followed the Germans as they returned to their bases and claimed two dive bombers shot down for the loss of both Yugoslav aircraft.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}}\n[[File:Bombed National Library Belgrad.JPG|thumb|250px|left|A 2008 photograph of the ruins of the National Library of Serbia, bombed on 6 April 1941|alt=an overgrown crater with ruined walls around part of the perimeter]]\nBelgrade was targeted on two other occasions on the first day of the invasion. The third wave struck at 14:00, consisting of 94 twin-engined bombers flying from airfields near [[Vienna]], escorted by 60 fighters. This wave was met by eighteen fighters of the 6th Fighter Regiment, which claimed four German aircraft. The fourth attack of the day approached Belgrade at 16:00, comprising 97 dive bombers and 60 fighters.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}}\n\nThe Germans claimed nineteen Yugoslav Bf 109E fighters and four unidentified aircraft destroyed on 6 April. Actual Yugoslav aircraft losses on the first day were ten shot down and fifteen damaged. The Yugoslavs claimed to have shot down twenty-two German aircraft and forced two others to land. The Germans lost twelve aircraft, significantly fewer than claimed by the Yugoslavs: two Do 17Z light bombers, five Bf 110 heavy fighters, four Ju 87 dive bombers, and one Bf 109E fighter.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}} One Luftwaffe pilot who claimed his first victory over Belgrade on 6 April was ''[[Oberleutnant]]'' [[Gerhard Koall]] of [[Jagdgeschwader 54|''Jagdgeschwader'' 54]].{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|p=199}} He went on to be credited with 37 victories and was awarded the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross]] in 1944.{{sfn|Fellgiebel|2000|p=216}}\n\nGerman bombers and dive-bombers dropped {{convert|215|-|360|LT|ST}} of [[aerial bomb|bombs]] and [[Incendiary device|incendiaries]] on the capital.{{sfn|Zajac|1993|p=31}}{{sfn|Knell|2009|p=194}} The weak VVKJ and inadequate anti-aircraft defences of Belgrade briefly attempted to meet the overwhelming Luftwaffe assault, but were eliminated as threats during the first wave of the attack. Sources vary regarding the success achieved by the defenders. A US Army study first published in 1953 states that the Luftwaffe lost two fighter aircraft, downed 20 Yugoslav aircraft and destroyed a further 44 on the ground.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p=49}} The military historian Daniel L. Zajac writes that the Germans lost 40 aircraft during the two-day air battle.{{sfn|Zajac|1993|p=31}} Another source indicates the loss of 14 German aircraft on 6 April.{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=200\u2013208}} Dive-bombers in subsequent waves were able to operate at rooftop altitude.{{sfn|U.S. Army|1986|p=49}}\n\nAccording to the historian [[Stevan K. Pavlowitch]], the bombing of Belgrade lasted three days.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=17}} Other sources state the air battle over Belgrade lasted only two days owing to poor flying conditions on 8 April.{{sfn|Zajac|1993|p=31}} The most important cultural institution that was destroyed was the [[National Library of Serbia]], which was hit by bombs and gutted by fire. Hundreds of thousands of rare books, maps, and [[medieval]] manuscripts were destroyed.{{sfn|Norris|2008|p=41}} Also struck was the [[Belgrade Zoo]], sending frightened animals running through the streets.{{sfn|Freeman|2008|p=94}}\n\n==British retaliation==\n[[No. 37 Squadron RAF|No. 37 Squadron]] of the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) conducted two bombing raids on [[Sofia]], the capital of Bulgaria, in retaliation for the bombing of Belgrade. Operating [[Vickers Wellington]] bombers from an airfield in [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]], the squadron conducted raids on 6/7 April and 12/13 April, dropping a total of {{convert|30|LT|ST}} of high-explosive bombs on railway targets and nearby residential areas. These raids were carried out despite the fact that Britain was not at war with Bulgaria until 12 December 1941. The historian Herman Knell calls the retaliatory justification for these raids \"strange and implausible\".{{sfn|Knell|2009|p=195}} The aviation historians Shores, Cull and Malizia indicate that these raids were attacks on the lines of communication of German forces attacking Greece and Yugoslavia, and note that the raid on 6/7 April targeted an ammunition train and other installations in Sofia, and the raid on 12/13 April bombed the railway marshalling yards. Other similar targets in Bulgaria were attacked by the RAF during the [[Balkans Campaign (World War II)|Balkans Campaign]].{{sfn|Shores|Cull|Malizia|1987|pp=232, 243}}\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\n[[File:Spomenik pilotima 1941.JPG|thumb|200px|Monument to the Yugoslav pilots killed during Operation Retribution, located in [[New Belgrade]]|alt=rectangular polished dark stone plinth pointing toward the sky, with a winged plaque and inscription at the base]]\nThe bombing of Belgrade paralyzed communications between the Yugoslav military and its headquarters, and contributed decisively to the rapid collapse of Yugoslav resistance.{{sfn|Boog|Krebs|Vogel|2006|p=366}} Civilian casualties were significant, but sources vary widely from 1,500 to 17,000 killed.{{sfn|Knell|2009|pp=194\u2013195}} They were worsened by the disclosure of air-raid shelter locations to the Germans in the days preceding the attack.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}} The official casualty figure released by the occupation authorities soon after the bombing was 2,271 killed. Other sources mention 5,000 to 10,000 fatalities, and later Yugoslav estimates ranged even higher.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=16}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=18}} The historian [[Jozo Tomasevich]] writes that the higher estimates were downgraded following \"careful postwar investigations\", and indicates that a figure between 3,000 and 4,000 is more realistic.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=74}}\n\nBelgrade was occupied on 13 April 1941, and four days later, Yugoslavia capitulated.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=19}} Afterwards, Luftwaffe engineers conducted a bomb damage assessment in Belgrade. The report stated that {{convert|218.5|MT}} of bombs were dropped, 10 to 14 percent being incendiaries. It listed all the targets of the bombing, mentioned that seven aerial mines were dropped, and that areas in the centre and northwest of the city had been destroyed, comprising 20 to 25 percent of its total area. Some aspects of the bombing remain unexplained, particularly the use of the aerial mines.{{sfn|Boog|Krebs|Vogel|2006|p=366}} Significant damage was done to Belgrade, particularly to the water and electrical systems.{{sfn|Terzi\u0107|1982|p=286}} Pavlowitch states that almost 50 percent of housing in Belgrade was destroyed.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=17\u201318}} After the invasion, the Germans forced between 3,500 and 4,000 [[Jews]] to collect rubble that was caused by the bombing.{{sfn|Ramet|2006|p=131}} Unexploded German bombs continue to be unearthed in the 21st century.{{sfn|Nikolic 28 July 2015}}\n\nL\u00f6hr was captured by the [[Yugoslav Partisans]] on 9 May 1945, escaped, and was recaptured on 13 May. He was intensively interrogated, after which he was tried before a Yugoslav military court on war crimes charges, one of which related to his command of ''Luftflotte'' IV during Operation Retribution. L\u00f6hr was convicted by the Yugoslav military court and sentenced to death.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=756\u2013757}} He was executed on 26 February 1947.{{sfn|Barbier|2017|p=155}} Following the invasion, Kren was appointed head of the [[Air Force of the Independent State of Croatia]] ({{lang-hr|Zrakoplovstvo Nezavisne Dr\u017eave Hrvatske}}, ZNDH). He was arrested in Italy in March 1947 and extradited to Yugoslavia, where he was tried on unrelated charges of war crimes for his role in the targeting of civilians by the ZNDH. He was found guilty on all counts and executed in 1948.{{sfn|Go\u00f1i|2002|p=236}}\n\nThe bombing of Belgrade was depicted in the 1980 Yugoslav feature film ''[[Who's Singin' Over There?]]'' ({{lang-sh|Ko to tamo peva|link=no}}) and the 1995 feature film ''[[Underground (1995 film)|Underground]]'' ({{lang-sh|Podzemlje|link=no}}).{{sfn|Goulding|2002|pp=167\u2013168, 186}} It is also the subject of [[Miodrag Pavlovi\u0107]]'s poem ''Belgrade 1941'' ({{lang-sh|Beograd 1941|link=no}}).{{sfn|Norris|2008|p=124}} The [[Serbian American]] poet [[Charles Simic]], a survivor of the bombing, wrote a poem titled ''Cameo Appearance'' recounting his experiences.{{sfn|Forhan|2008|pp=255\u2013256}} A monument commemorating the Yugoslav pilots killed during Operation Retribution was inaugurated in [[New Belgrade]] on 6 April 1997. It was designed by the sculptor [[Miodrag \u017divkovi\u0107 (sculptor)|Miodrag \u017divkovi\u0107]].{{sfn|Glas javnosti 29 July 2005}} On 6 April 2016, the 75th anniversary of the bombing, a memorial service was held for the victims, attended by the Serbian [[Ministry of Labour, Employment, Veteran and Social Policy (Serbia)|Minister for Labour, Employment, Veteran and Social Policy]], [[Aleksandar Vulin]].{{sfn|B92 6 April 2016}} In June 2017, it was announced that the site containing the ruined foundations of the National Library of Serbia would be transformed into a memorial garden.{{sfn|Radio Television of Serbia 25 June 2017}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n\n'''Books'''\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Barbier\n  | first = Mary Kathryn\n  | year = 2017\n  | title = Spies, Lies, and Citizenship: The Hunt for Nazi Criminals\n  | publisher = University of Nebraska Press\n  | location = Lincoln, Nebraska\n  | isbn = 978-1-61234-973-2\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=IK8yDwAAQBAJ\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last1 = Boog\n  | first1 = Horst\n  | authorlink1 = Horst Boog\n  | last2 = Krebs\n  | first2 = Gerhard\n  | last3 = Vogel\n  | first3 = Detlef\n  | authorlink3 = Detlef Vogel\n  | year = 2006\n  | title = Germany and the Second World War: Volume VII: The Strategic Air War in Europe and the War in the West and East Asia, 1943\u20131944/5\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | location = Oxford, England\n  | isbn = 978-1-280-75877-5\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rVVeO4B985wC\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Chant\n  | first = Christopher\n  | year = 1986\n  | title = The Encyclopedia of Codenames of World War II\n  | publisher = Routledge\n  | location = London\n  | isbn = 978-0-415-71087-9\n  | ref = harv\n  }}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Fellgiebel\n  | first = Walther-Peer\n  | authorlink = Walther-Peer Fellgiebel\n  | year = 2000\n  | title = Die Tr\u00e4ger des Ritterkreuzes des Eisernen Kreuzes 1939\u20131945 \u2013 Die Inhaber der h\u00f6chsten Auszeichnung des Zweiten Weltkrieges aller Wehrmachtsteile\n  |trans-title = The Bearers of the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross 1939\u20131945 \u2013 The Owners of the Highest Award of the Second World War of all Wehrmacht Branches\n  | language = German\n  | publisher = Podzun-Pallas\n  | location = Friedberg, Germany\n  | isbn = 978-3-7909-0284-6\n  | ref = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n  | last = Freeman\n  | first = Gregory A.\n  | year = 2008\n  | title = The Forgotten 500: The Untold Story of the Men Who Risked All for the Greatest Rescue Mission of World War II\n  | publisher = Penguin Books\n  | location = New York\n  | isbn = 978-0-451-22495-8\n  | url = https://books.google.c